<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Trade Arrangement between S. Africa, Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's captains of industry
Wednesday welcomed the increase in export quotas to South Africa
as a step toward improving trade relations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean Industry and Commerce Minister Nathan Shamuyarira
and his South African counterpart Alec Erwin met last Thursday in
Bulawayo, Zimbabwe's second largest city and agreed to review
existing quotas under the 1964 Trade Agreement in light of their
utilization by exporters and benefits to the Zimbabwean economy.
</P>
<P>
The revised quotas, effective from August 1, are an interim
measure to pave the way for the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) Trade Protocol expected to come into force on
January 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
The products approved for revision included yarn which
increased from 800,000 kgs per annum to 2,000,000 kgs, blankets
from 40,000 units to 150, 000 units, household linen from 145,000
to 245,000.
</P>
<P>
The clothing quota remained at 3,127,000 units.
</P>
<P>
President of the Zimbabwe National Chamber of Commerce Nhlanhla
Masuku Wednesday said that the move was a step in the right
direction.
</P>
<P>
"The best area should have been for tariff reductions without
quotas. I suspect the South Africans are waiting for the SADC
Trade Protocol. The quotas will definitely have an effect on
export earnings from South Africa, no doubt about that," he said.
</P>
<P>
Economist of the Confederation of Zimbabwe Industries Farai
Zizhou also said the increased quotas were "welcome" and a "good
starting point".
</P>
<P>
"Obviously our trade includes a lot more products than just
those mentioned. The South Africans are looking at limitations to
what they can do in light of certain problems with the trade
agreement itself," he said.
</P>
<P>
He noted the move was an interim arrangement because under the
bilateral agreement, tariffs on clothing were at 30 percent but
under terms of the SADC Trade Protocol it would be 35 percent but
with no quotas.
</P>
<P>
After that, he said, South Africa would reduce tariffs by five
percentage points every year.
</P>
<P>
Trade between the two countries has been haunted by trade
imbalances with Zimbabwe importing goods worth 13 billion
Zimbabwean dollars (342 million U.S. dollars) while South Africa
imported only three billion Zimbabwean dollars (78 million U.S.
dollars) worth of goods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
