<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Economy Turns to Positive: Statistics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Thai economy has turned to
positive in April and May with 4.9 percent and 1.4 percent growth
rates respectively, said a statement issued by the Thai Finance
Ministry on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
However, the statement said, Thai economy still posed an
overall 1.5 percent contraction in the first five months of this
year due to the negative growth of 6.5 percent, 5.4 percent and
3.6 percent in January, February and March consequently.
</P>
<P>
The economic rehabilitation of Thailand resulted from
increasing domestic consumption and investment, which were spurred
by the government's economic stimulus package, the statement
noted.
</P>
<P>
Inflation in the first half of this year rose by 1.1 percent,
much slower than the level of 9.7 percent in the same period of
last year, it said.
</P>
<P>
The country's exports in June increased for the third
consecutive month, reaching 4.85 billion U.S. dollars, a 4.8
percent year-on-year growth from 1998, and a 3.28 percent growth
from May, the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
