<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek, Bulgarian Premiers Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis
Wednesday held talks with his visiting Bulgarian counterpart, Ivan
Kostov, to discuss bilateral relations, cooperation in the Balkan
region and Sofia's bid to join the European Union (EU) and the
North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
Both premiers agreed that the works provided in the stability
pact for the Balkan region should go ahead at a rapid pace and the
pact should not aim at tackling isolated problems but rather than
those of the Balkans as a whole.
</P>
<P>
They stressed that the criterion for dealing with the Balkan
problems should be the rules of international law, the
international treaties in force and that the United Nations should
play a more active role.
</P>
<P>
The two men also agreed to submit joint proposals within the
framework of the stability pact for the Balkans and to support the
construction of highway 4 which will connect southeastern Europe
with the rest of the continent.
</P>
<P>
While paying great attention to bilateral relations, Simitis
and Kostov said that they were opposed to any change of borders in
the Balkans or in Europe in general.
</P>
<P>
Simitis also voiced Geece's support in Bulgaria's effort to
join the EU and NATO.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Kostov said that Bulgaria supported the
construction of the Burgas-Alexandroupoli oil pipeline and was
ready to meet the Greek and Russian sides at the end of July to
form the joint venture
</P>
<P>
Kostov, who arrived here Wednesday for an official two-day
visit, will also meet with Greek President Costis Stephanopoulos
and Parliament President Apostolos Kaklamanis Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
