<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Retail Sales Slow Down in Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON July 21 (Xinhua) Retail sales in Britain remained at the
same level in June as they were in May, but growth over the past
year has exceeded expectation, according to official figures on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Office of National Statistics (ONS) said that over the
year, sales were up 3.8 percent - the biggest rise since May 1998.
Market analysts had been expecting a monthly rise of 0.4 percent
and a year-on-year rise of 3.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The ONS said the latest figures confirmed that the underlying
rate of sales growth had picked up since the turn of the year but
did not necessarily point to a further pick-up in growth.
</P>
<P>
It is also believed that the strong year-on-year figure was
mainly due to a weak performance in June 1998 rather than a strong
performance in June 1999.
</P>
<P>
Economists say the June figures suggest retailers have been
making discounts to boost sales. Some argued that the Bank of
England's interest rate cut in June may have been an error.
</P>
</TEXT>
