<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Millenium Bug Can Be Arrested: Expert </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 21 (Xinhua) -- A United Kingdom-based engineer
working on coordinating the Y2K millenium bug (Year 2000 computer
compliance) project said Wednesday that it is possible to overcome
the new millenium bug and avert threats it poses.
</P>
<P>
Richard Earp, who is heading an operational policy development
group in England, said in an interview with the Zimbabwe News
Agency here that it is not possible for governments and task
forces to solve the millenium bug problem alone.
</P>
<P>
There is need for lower levels to know the problem and they
should try to solve it on their own, he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Earp said the role of external task forces should be to check
on organizations, advise and possibly bring sanctions to
organizations that do not work toward solving the problem.
</P>
<P>
He said though it is possible to solve the threats of the
millenium bug, organizations should not be complacent and not to
over-react.
</P>
<P>
Earp is one of the speakers attending a two-day workshop on how
the effects of the millenium bug could be minimized for the
critical sectors in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Participants will map out contingency plans for possible
adoption by the targeted sectors.
</P>
<P>
At the opening ceremony of the workshop Wednesday, Zimbabwean
Higher Education and Technical Training Minister Ignatius Chombo
said the National Y2K Task Force was in the process of carrying
out an analysis on key sectors in the country to determine their
preparedness.
</P>
<P>
He said the findings from the studies were intended to help
interested parties to put in place corrective steps to avoid total
systems failures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
