<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak FM Calls for Meaningful Indo-Pak Dialogue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister
Sartaj Aziz Wednesday called on India to restore the Line of
Control (LoC) in Kashmir and resume meaningful dialogue with
Pakistan to resolve the Kashmir dispute.
</P>
<P>
India cannot expect Pakistan to respect the LoC but itself
continues to violate it by moving into the Pakistan-held Kashmir,
Aziz said at the conclusion of the National Assembly debate on
Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
He said it is vital for peace in South Asia that the LoC,
accepted by the two sides under the 1972 Simla Agreement, should
be respected by both India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Referring to a statement by Indian Foreign Minister Jaswant
Singh on trust between the two neighbors, Aziz said, "Real trust
between India and Pakistan had never existed throughout the past
52 years."
</P>
<P>
Singh, in an earlier statement, said India is not ready to
resume talks with Pakistan because it, by backing intrusion into
Indian-held Kashmir, had betrayed India's trust.
</P>
<P>
Aziz further pointed out that it is India that had repeatedly
damaged the prospects of building a relationship of trust by using
force or coercion to resolve issues that arose between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
To explain, the foreign minister said the Indians had violated
the LoC separately at Chorbatla in 1972, at Siachin glacier in
1984 and at Qamar in 1988.
</P>
<P>
"Today Kashmir is a flash point and fully engages the attention
of the world community, " Aziz said, adding that "a just and final
settlement of the issue cannot be delayed any longer."
</P>
<P>
He urged the United Nations and the major powers to play their
roles to facilitate a "meaningful dialogue" between India and
Pakistan, "a dialogue that leads to a final solution of the
Kashmir issue."
</P>
<P>
"We do not need dialogue for sake of dialogue. We do not need
yet another process of sterile and unproductive talks," stated the
foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
He said Pakistan would like to revive the Lahore process with a
meaningful and result-oriented dialogue to resolve all issues that
divide the two South Asian countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
