<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek, Cyprus Officials Discuss Cyprus Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Greece's Alternate Foreign Minister
Yiannos Kranidiotis Wednesday discussed with visiting Cyprus
Foreign Minister Yiannakis Kasoulides the Cyprus problem and the
island's relations with the European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
Speaking after their talks, Kranidiotis criticized the visit
by Turkish Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit to northern Cyprus this
week, saying that this undermined the attempt at Greek-Turkish
talks on low-level issues, with the first meeting to take place in
Ankara next Monday.
</P>
<P>
However, Kranidiotis hoped there would a positive outcome from
the talks that could have a run-off effect on larger issues, such
as the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Kranidiotis urged the international community not to hold the
island republic to a double standard but to assist in finding a
solution to the divided island by exerting pressure on Turkey.
</P>
<P>
He also asked neighboring Turkey to change its stance and
respond to its international obligations by encouraging talks on
the creation of a bizonal, bicommunal federation with one
international identity and nationality.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus's accession course toward the EU should proceed
regardless of the present political problem, he added.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Kasoulides called on the international community
not to accept any of the demands pursued by Ecevit concerning the
recognization of northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
He said that if developments moved within the framework of the
G-8 communique providing for talks without preconditions, there
was a real hope of settling the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriots-controlled
south and the Turkish Cypriots-dominated north since 1974 when
Turkish troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the
island in the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
</TEXT>
