<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angolan Rebels Attack City Near Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The General Staff of the Angolan
Armed Forces Wednesday confirmed that the rebel UNITA troops
attacked Catete City, 63 kms southeast of capital Luanda Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, the general staff said in a statement that the
government army has defeated the troops of the National Union for
Total Independence of Angola (UNITA).
</P>
<P>
The statement said it was the first time that the rebels has
attacked a city so close to the capital since the civil war
renewed late last year.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, an unknown number of UNITA troops
attacked Catete in the central part of Bengo Province around 4:00
a.m. Tuesday, killing two government soldiers, wounding six
civilians and destroying three civilian vehicles.
</P>
<P>
The government army immediately launched counter-attack. The
fighting lasted for some four hours before the army chased the
rebels out to the northwest.
</P>
<P>
The statement did not mention the casualties of the rebels.
</P>
<P>
But according to eyewitnesses fleeing from the city, many
people were forced to flee toward Luanda for fear of the UNITA
rebels.
</P>
<P>
The fighting between the UNITA troops and the government army
used to take place hundreds of kilometers away from the capital
city.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the situation in the central cities of Huambo and
Kuito has been relatively calm.
</P>
<P>
However, Angolan government officials said that the rebels are
stepping up attacks on minor cities and towns in order to foil the
government offensive during the dry season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
