<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Ruling Body to Approve Leadership Plan on Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The ruling General Council of the
World Trade Organization (WTO) will formally approve a
power-sharing plan to appoint Mike Moore of New Zealand and
Supachai Panitchpakdi of Thailand as the WTO's next two consecutive
leaders, according to trade sources.
</P>
<P>
During an informal meeting Tuesday at the WTO headquarters,
trade envoys of the WTO's 134 members discussed the draft "3+3"
plan brokered by Bangladesh and Australia.
</P>
<P>
Although no participants said that they really liked the plan,
none of them said they were opposed to it, meaning that the plan
was effectively accepted, officials said at the end of Tuesday's
meeting.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposal, Mike Moore of New Zealand would be the WTO
Director-General for three years from September 1, 1999 to August
31, 2002. Supachai Panitchpakdi of Thailand would succeed Moore
from September 1, 2002 for three years to August 31, 2005.
</P>
<P>
Neither of the candidates should be eligible for reappointment
as Director-General nor should his period of office be extended,
according to the proposal. It stressed that the special
arrangement for the two candidates should not be the precedent for
future appointments of the WTO chief.
</P>
<P>
Normally, the term of office of the WTO chief is four years
like former WTO Director-General Renato Ruggiero has served.
</P>
<P>
The remaining problems now appear to be the number of the
deputy director-generals and their allocation among different
geographical regions but they will not prevent the WTO members
from reaching consensus around the arrangement of the top
leadership. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-21 17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OPEC Urged to Discuss Upward Trend of Oil Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Oil experts here urged on
Wednesday the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC)
to hold an emergency meeting to deal with the present upward trend
of the oil prices in the world market.
</P>
<P>
In interviews with the Kuwait News Agency, the experts, who
declined to be named, suggested that OPEC members meet to reach a
formula protecting their interests, in case other oil producers
take advantage of the current market situation.
</P>
<P>
They said the oil cartel should act quickly, because it was not
in the interest of the member states that prices reach very high
levels.
</P>
<P>
The oil prices witnessed record rise recently in global markets
touching the highest level ever since November 1997, mainly due to
the adherence of OPEC states to the output reductions they agreed
last March.
</P>
<P>
"Whenever oil prices are moderate, OPEC is in the safe-side,"
the experts said.
</P>
<P>
They underlined that OPEC must play an active role in the oil
markets whenever prices begin to climb up or drop down, adding
that they should agree on price limits.
</P>
<P>
They warned that if OPEC members fail to move quickly other oil
producing nations will "take advantage and accomplish projects and
maintenance of their oil fields to pump more oil into the world
markets."
</P>
<P>
The experts also attributed the current price rise to the increase
of oil demand in Asia, maintenance on North Sea fields and the
shrinking world oil stocks.
</P>
<P>
They also expected that the oil prices would rise to about 20
U.S. dollars per barrel, as winter is coming and demand will
increase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Europeans See Internet Part of Daily Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Europeans are more and more
interested in using Internet for doing things as part of their
daily life despite of their slower pace for embracing information
society than that in the United States.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey shows that many European citizens rely
increasingly on the use of new Information Technology (IT)
applications. For the interviewed Europeans, 47.8 percent usually
consult local town or council services from their home in order to
get documents they need.
</P>
<P>
The European Union's Eurobarometer survey said that 42.3
percent of respondents show their interest in preparing a complete
trip from home on a computer screen, while 41.9 get a doctor's
advice on a health problem.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, many Europeans choose an easy way to look for a job
by consulting the employment office from a computer. The survey
showed 41.5 percent seek their jobs from Internet and 33.9 learn a
training program from a computer or television at home as if
attending the course in person.
</P>
<P>
Some Europeans believe that the worthiest spending for using
Internet is distance learning. Some 18.2 percent of the
interviewed, an equivalent of 56 million European citizens,
expressed their willingness to pay 10 euros (10.4 U.S. dollars)
per month to get such a service.
</P>
<P>
The data showed Internet users in Europe have doubled since
early 1997. Now, about 27 million people use the Internet at home
and some 22.4 million use it at work.
</P>
<P>
Currently, an average of 8.3 percent of private households in
the 15-nation European Union have Internet access, compared to 4.4
percent in 1997. However, the contrast is obvious in the whole
picture of the 15-country bloc. The leading countries using the
Internet are Sweden (39.6 percent), Denmark (24.6 percent) and the
Netherlands (19.6 percent), while the less active countries are
Greece (2.9 percent), Portugal (3.4 percent), France (3.9 percent)
and Spain (5 percent).
</P>
<P>
But for Internet companies and commercial banks, they are happy
to see the growing passion for Internet in Europe. Last week, a
two-month old Internet firm, Funmail, announced its listing plan.
The company providing fun and strange E-mail addresses has lured
about 45,000 Internet surfers since it established two months ago.
Observers said Funmail has the right sight over the prospects of
Internet investment by Europeans.
</P>
<P>
For America Online Inc. (AOL), the unchallenged leader in
cyberspace access in the United States, keeping up with growth in
Europe is important. While AOL still has plenty of room to grow in
the United States, where about 37 percent of households are
on-line, the potential is even higher in Europe, analysts said.
According to the Jupiter Communications, only 13 percent of
households are on-line in Germany and only 4 percent in Italy.
</P>
<P>
Banks are also trying to tap their businesses to cater for the
Internet fever. Some bankers say they would do their businesses on
the Internet while viewing the European market as a whole.
Observers believe the on-line banking will be the best way to tap
the market in European.
</P>
<P>
The on-line businesses of Several banks in the Nordic countries
are in full swing. Sweden's SEB bank started its Internet services
at the end of 1996 when they expected some 10,000 clients, but
they were surprised to see ten times of the figure six months
later. Now on-line customers accounted for 20 percent of SEB's
total retail services.
</P>
<P>
With the development of information society, Europeans would be
easy to find that the Internet makes their life easier since
E-mail, E-commerce, E-shopping, E-course and other E-led
activities and services have already entered their daily life,
though some countries are still reluctant to push ahead with the
trend in the continent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Pledges $150 M for Yugoslav Reconstruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Russia said Wednesday that it will
allocate 150 million U.S. dollars in loans to help rebuild
Yugoslavia's economy ravaged by NATO's 78-day bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
The loan will be used to finance the delivery of Russian
equipment, goods and services, Russian Economics Minister Andrei
Shapovaliants told a news conference announcing a government
resolution on the Balkan country's reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet will set up a commission supervising Russia's
involvement in rebuilding the Yugoslav economy, the Interfax news
agency quoted Shapovaliants as saying.
</P>
<P>
The government has approved a plan of urgent steps aimed at
rebuilding the Yugoslav economy, especially the supplies of
natural gas and technical aid to rebuilding priority assets.
</P>
<P>
Diesel fuel and gasoline will be sent to Yugoslavia as a
priority to insure the timely harvesting and processing of crops.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
