<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-21 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt's 91 Percent of Businesses in Private </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Egypt's private sector accounts for
91 percent of the country's total businesses and employs about 10
million of its 17 million-strong labor force, according to a
census released on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The economic census for 1996-97 revealed that Egypt had 3.078
million businesses, but only 1.691 million of them are
operational, said Ihab Alawi, head of the Central Organization for
Statistics and Mobilization.
</P>
<P>
Of the operational businesses, 1.541 million, or 91.4 percent,
are run by the private sector; the government and public sector
control the rest, Alawi told a news conference announcing the
results of the economic census, conduced in one and half years,
and an update of the 1998 population census.
</P>
<P>
The private sector employed a total of 10.354 million people
out of 17.147 million in the labor force, he said.
</P>
<P>
Alawi added, however, that only about 15 million people are
officially counted as part of the country's work force. The
remainder are not officially included because they are completing
military service or are part of an official sector such as fruit
sellers operating from street carts.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's unemployment rate is 8.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Comparative figures from previous years were not available as
this was the first extensive economic census performed, Alawi said.
</P>
<P>
With the launching of an ambitious economic reform and
structural adjustment program in 1991, Egypt has pushed private
sector development and is attempting to privatize its public
sector companies.
</P>
<P>
The census showed that the government employs a total of 4.364
million people and that 876,729 people work for public sector
firms.
</P>
<P>
The largest private sector employers are the agricultural and
fisheries industries, which employ 4.404 million people.
</P>
<P>
Alawi also released updated population statistics, placing the
country's population at 63,915,319 people as of January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The figures, an update of census statistics from January 1,
1998, include 1.9 million Egyptians living abroad. Alawi said the
population is growing by about 1,287,480 people per year, or 3,527
per day.
</P>
<P>
The annual population growth rate in 1998 was 2.099 percent.
Egypt had projected an annual population growth of 1.8 percent for
the 1990s, which it hoped to decrease in following decades.
</P>
<P>
Alawi said the larger than anticipated growth rate was not an
indication that the population planning measures had failed, but
that the death rate had declined and life expectancy rose.
</P>
<P>
The government is encouraging family planning to reduce the
population growth, which is eating away into its social and
economic development plans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-21 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Algeria, Yemen Agree on Holding Arab Summit to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Algerian President Abdul-Aziz
Bouteflika and his Yemeni counterpart Ali Abdullah Saleh have
agreed on the necessity of holding an Arab summit to restore Arab
solidarity to face the current challenges.
</P>
<P>
The proposed summit aims to heal the rift of the Arab rank, the
to presidents said in a joint press conference after their
political talks here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
They asserted their determination to go ahead with the efforts
to hold an Arab summit for rapprochement.
</P>
<P>
Algeria and Yemen support the Arab national causes in all
weathers, Bouteflika said, pointing out that there were Arab calls
to achieve full or gradual regional rapprochement.
</P>
<P>
He urged for strengthening the Arab-African ties, expressing
satisfaction with the resolution of the Yemeni-Eritrean dispute
peacefully.
</P>
<P>
On the Algerian-Yemeni bilateral ties Bouteflika and Saleh
agreed on enchancing them in all fields.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed on reviving the work of the Joint Ministerial
Committee that is proposed to convene its sixth session in Algiers next
November.
</P>
<P>
There are ten cooperation accords between the two countries
that are awaiting signing, the Algerian leader said, urging the
Yemeni business people to visit Algeria and invest in it.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday Saleh held talks with Bouteflika on several
issues including the bilateral ties and the developments on the
Arab, African and international arenas.
</P>
<P>
The yemeni president left here Wednesday afternoon after a
two-day state visit to Algeria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
