<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Wants to Scrap Mir, Focus on ISS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Deputy Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov
said here Wednesday that Russia should scrap its Mir space station
and focus its limited resources on its role in the International
Space Station project.
</P>
<P>
The 13-year-old Mir has fulfilled its task and has exhausted
its resources, and there is evidence it is becoming decrepit, the
Interfax news agency quoted Klebanov as saying.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the state is no longer able to pay the annual 250
million U.S. dollars to keep the station operating, he said.
</P>
<P>
Klebanov said Russia should now concentrate on the ISS project.
Russia has undertaken to provide 11 of the future station's 36
component units and 33 percent of its operation time would be at
Russia's disposal.
</P>
<P>
He said the ISS could not materialize without Russian
participation and that meeting its commitments for the project was
a "matter of honor" for Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
