<HEADLINE> Russian Navy Denies Presence of Chemical Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Navy on Wednesday
denied a Norwegian newspaper report that its Northern Fleet keeps
chemical weapons in a top-secret depot near the Norwegian border
in Murmansk region.
</P>
<P>
"No chemical weapons are stored at any storage facilities or
bases of the Russian Navy," the Interfax news agency quoted the
navy's press service as saying in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The report in the Norwegian newspaper Verdens Gang (VG) caused
"great concern" among the navy command, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, the Russian Foreign Ministry and Norwegian
environmentalists also refuted the reported presence of chemical
weapons near the Norwegian border.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Vladimir Rakhmanin said Russia has
honored its international commitments and published information on
all its chemical stockpiles and their locations.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for Bellona, a Norwegian environmental
organization, said the group "does not possess any information
that there is a storage facility for chemical weapon components
near Severomorsk and believes the report to that effect in the
Norwegian newspaper VG not to be true," Interfax reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
