<HEADLINE> Israel Urged to Implement Agreements Signed with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Jordan expressed hope on Wednesday
that Israel will implement the frozen agreements signed with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Jordan hoped that Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak would succeed in seeking steps to
implement the signed agreements, especially the Wye River accord,
Jordanian Foreign Minister Abdel-Ilah al-Khatib said.
</P>
<P>
Al-Khatib was speaking to reporters after a meeting with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak along with Abdul-Karim Kabariti,
Jordan's chief of the royal palace.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian officials arrived in Cairo earlier in the day for
a brief visit, during which they conveyed a message to Mubarak
from Jordanian King Abdullah on the Mideast peace process. They
also discussed with the Egyptian leader various ways to revive the
Palestinian-Israeli peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Al-Khatib said the implementation of the signed agreement is
the key to the success of the peacemaking.
</P>
<P>
Al-Khatib's call came amid Arab anxiety over Barak's proposal
to fold the Wye land-for-security agreement into the final status
negotiations, rather than implement it immediately. The
Palestinians have rejected Barak's proposal.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the agreement is the key to making the peace
process succeed," Al-Khatib said.
</P>
<P>
The Wye agreement, signed last October, calls for Israeli troop
withdrawals from a further 13.1 percent of the West Bank and the
release of Palestinian prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Former Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu froze the
implementation in December but Barak promised to revive the
agreement in his election campaign. 
