<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Accused of Actively Training Rwandan Hutu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 21 (Xinhua) - More details have emerged about the
 recruitment and training of Rwandan ''Interahamwe'' militia and
defeated former Rwandan government soldiers (ex-FAR), the Rwanda
News Agency (RNA) claimed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"It is no secret that the Republic of Zimbabwe has been
actively training members of the ex-FAR and Interahamwe militia,"
Rwandan army spokesman, Major Emmanuel Ndahiro, was quoted as
telling the RNA Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan army official's accusations followed declarations by
Rwandan Vice-President, Major General Paul Kagame, who accused
Zimbabwe of actively training the Hutu militia with the objective
of sending them to Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
A statement issued early this week by the Office of the
President also expressed concern over "the continued training of
the Interahamwe militia in Zimbabwe and their deployment in Congo
(K)," which it said was in violation of the Lusaka Accord signed
on July 10
</P>
<P>
Well-informed sources in Kigali, quoting Zimbabwean and Rwandan
 "Interahamwe'' POWs, told RNA that the first group of trainees
mobilized and retrained were mainly former air-force pilots and
mechanics who were taken to Gweru Air-Force Base in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
They included Celestin Nzeyimana, former presidential jet
technician, and Maj. Kalisa (only one name), a pilot in ex-FAR and
many others.
</P>
<P>
"Full relations with ex-FAR and Interahamwe were established in
October 1998 when more than 30 former Rwandan politicians and
ex-FAR officials were given political asylum to assist the war
effort in Congo (K)," the sources told RNA.
</P>
<P>
More recruits have been arriving from Nairobi (Kenya), Central
African Republic, South Africa and elsewhere, and include
well-known genocidal leaders like Selvain Nkunzurwanda who went to
Harare from Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
These recruits have been given Zimbabwean passports while
others from South Africa have been using refugee travel documents
delivered by the host country.
</P>
<P>
One cited by the sources is Captain Edisbald Maniraguha who is
said to have moved from Cape Town to Harare. He is said to have
been involved in arms trafficking for ex-FAR in Congo (K) from the
South African town.
</P>
<P>
It is said that some of these ex-FAR officers have been sent to
serve in the planning and operations staff of the allies in the
Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC), while others were assigned to
serve in the military intelligence structures in the Cranbourne
barracks in Harare.
</P>
<P>
So far at least 505 company commanders have allegedly received
training in Zimbabwe since January 1999, with Rwandan Hutu militia
disguised as Congolese soldiers at Gweru army college.
</P>
<P>
A Rwandan government official who asked not be named charged
that from March 1999, Zimbabwe expanded the training program
enormously and committed 33 million Zimbabwean dollars in January
to assist the Interahamwe and ex-FAR as well as Ugandan and
Burundi rebels which Zimbabwe want to use against the three
countries.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe, Namibia, and Angola, as well as Chad have been
fighting alongside Interahamwe militia in the DRC where they have
sent troops to prop up president Laurent Desire Kabila. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
