<HEADLINE> Airline Passenger Traffic to Grow through 2001 Globally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Scheduled passenger traffic
of the world airlines is expected to grow 4.1 percent in 1999, 5
percent in 2000 and 5.7 percent in 2001, according to the
International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Total international and domestic scheduled passenger traffic
generated by ICAO's 185 contracting states is forecast to rise to
2739 billion passenger-kilometers in 1999, ICAO said in a news
release issued by the U.N. Department of Public Information.
</P>
<P>
ICAO's 1998 figure was 2630 billion. It is expected to go up to
2875 billion in 2000 and 3038 billion in 2001.
</P>
<P>
Traffic in Asia/Pacific is expected to grow at the highest rate
among ICAO regions after a decline of 1.5 percent in 1998, said
ICAO, a 45-year-old specialized agency of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Seeing markets for European and Latin America/Caribbean
"reasonably buoyant", ICAO expects a close-to-the-average moderate
growth for the Middle East and Africa, and more moderate growth
for the mature North America airline markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
