<HEADLINE> Rwanda to Open 3 New Commercial Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 21 (RNA) - Three new commercial banks are soon
opening up banking services in Rwandan capital Kigali, bringing
the total number of banks operating in the country to 11, the
Rwanda News Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda has a total of seven commercial banks and one
cooperative bank which commands the biggest countryside network of
branches, a Rwandan central bank official was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Three groups have already applied for permission to open up
their commercial banks and the processes are in advanced stages,"
said Angelique Kantengwa, chief inspector of banks and other
financial institutions in the Central Bank of Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
She said that among the three groups which have sought
permission from the central bank, one of them has fulfilled over
90 percent of the requirements.
</P>
<P>
However, she declined to reveal the new springing banks.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda's current laws require a capital base of 285,000 U.S.
dollars for any banking group to qualify for setting up a
commercial bank.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that opening of the new banks and the growth of
the financial sector will facilitate the utilization of the
investment funding, and will boost economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
"The improvement of the financial institutions will address
medium and long-term lending problems," Kantengwa noted.
</P>
<P>
The central bank official condemned some local banks which
concentrate more on lending, while not caring about mobilizing
savings which is currently derived from very few clients and are
mainly short-term.
</P>
<P>
Rwanda is soon to enact a new law giving powers to the central
bank to decide, depending on the economic indicators, the amount
of capital necessary for setting up a financial institution.
</P>
<P>
The new banks have sprung up when the Rwandan franc has
witnessed a serious depreciation.
</P>
<P>
The value of the Rwandan francs against a U.S. dollar stood at
between 285-320 in 1994-1997, whereas in 1998-1999 its value has
been depreciated in the range of 330-365, while on the black
market the dollar was sold at 380 Rwanda francs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
