<HEADLINE> Mozambicans Urged to Support Anti-polio Drive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano Wednesday called upon the people to support the national
anti-polio drive.
</P>
<P>
"Polio must be wiped out," the president said in his message to
the nation.
</P>
<P>
The anti-polio campaign this year is scheduled to be
implemented in two stages: first one from July 26 to 30 and the
second from August 30 to September 3.
</P>
<P>
Some 3.3 million children under the age of five will be
vaccinated. The drive will cost some 1.9 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, in 1997, four polio cases
were reported and in 1990, only one was reported as compared to 60
reported cases in 1980.
</P>
<P>
President Chissano noted that the southern African country has
been carrying out its anti-polio drive nationwide since 1996.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, children aged five or six will this year be fed with
Vitamin A to strengthen their immunity and eyesight.
</P>
<P>
The World Health Organization has targeted to wipe out the
childhood disease by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
At the 41st congress of the World Health Organization in May
1988, the Mozambican government promised to root up polio by 2000.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
