<HEADLINE> Orient House Remains Opened Under </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Israeli and Palestinian
officials agreed on Wednesday that the Orient House, Palestinian
headquarters in east Jerusalem, will continue to operate
according to the peace accords between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached after Israeli Public Security
Minister Shlomo Ben-Ami held talks with Faisal Husseini, chief
Palestinian official over Jerusalem affairs, for two hours at a
hotel in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Following the meeting, both Ben-Ami and Husseini said the
agreement opened a new chapter for the negotiations over Jerusalem
between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Ben-Ami said that there are still disputes over the Orient
House, but all problems will be resolved by dialogue, not by force.
</P>
<P>
Husseini praised the new Israeli government as "a government
of peace." He noted that the two sides will make efforts to find a
final settlement over the issue.
</P>
<P>
The dispute over the Orient House almost caused violent
clashes between Israeli security forces and the Palestinians two
months ago before Israel's May general elections.
</P>
<P>
Former Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu planned to
close three offices in the Orient House on the grounds that it was
violating a commitment of the Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
to abstain from political activity in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians rejected Netanyahu's accusation and warned
that there would be violent confrontations if Israel closed down
the offices by force.
</P>
<P>
After Ehud Barak, a moderate, won the Israeli prime ministerial
elections, he has pledged to end the Israeli-Arab conflicts by all
efforts. And the atmosphere in the peace process, soiled under the
three-year tenure of hard-line Netanyahu, has been improved.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians want the Arab-populated east Jerusalem, which
was seized by Israel in the 1967 Middle East war, as the capital
of a future Palestinian state, but Israel has insisted that
Jerusalem is its eternal and indivisible capital.
</P>
<P>
According to the existing peace accords, the two sides will
reach a settlement over the status Jerusalem in their final status
talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
