<HEADLINE> Egyptian Committee Approves Text of Strategic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 21 (Xinhua) -- An Egyptian ministerial committee on
Wednesday approved the text of a strategic agreement with the
European Union (EU).
</P>
<P>
The committee, which includes representatives from eight
ministries, approved the final form of the text of the Egyptian-EU
partnership agreement during a meeting in the day, Egypt's Middle
East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian Assistant Foreign Minister Gamal Bayoumi, who is the
chief negotiator for the agreement, said the text "contains big
privileges which were not enjoyed by any other country in the
agricultural and industrial fields."
</P>
<P>
The text "has secured balanced interests for Egypt and EU at
the political, economic and cultural levels," Bayoumi was quoted
by the news agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Egypt's export of agricultural products to
the EU will be increased by 252 percent, particularly potatoes,
oranges, raisins, peanuts and honey, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The draft package will be submitted to the cabinet in August
for approval and then to President Hosni Mubarak for a final say.
The agreement is expected to be signed in months.
</P>
<P>
After almost four years of negotiations, Egypt and the EU
reached the agreement last month. EU foreign ministers endorsed
the draft agreement on June 21.
</P>
<P>
The accord provides for more open trade, coordination in many
economic and financial areas, a political dialog and joint efforts
to combat money laundering and terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The accord is viewed to be part of an EU bid for a bigger
economic and political role in the region, where the 15-nation
European organization aims to have a free trade agreement with all
southern and eastern Mediterranean nations by 2010.
</P>
<P>
The EU is Egypt's largest trade partner, accounting for 638
million U.S. dollars of Egypt's exports and 3.6 billion dollars of
its imports in the first half of 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
