<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands of Congolese Refugees Fleeing Their </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 21 (Xinhua) -- More than 50,000 refugees have
been forced to flee Congo (Kinshasa) and Congo (Brazzaville) over
the last three weeks by the continued fighting in the two central
African countries.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugee (UNHCR) regional office
said in a press release here Wednesday that half of these new
refugees are from the east and north of the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC), where the conflict continues despite a peace
agreement signed on July 10 in Zambian capital Lusaka.
</P>
<P>
"Political solutions must be found urgently for the crises in
the two Congos," the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugee Sadako
Ogata was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
"The refugees and the hundreds of thousands of internally
displaced persons in both countries are suffering untold misery in
the absence of political solutions to the fighting in their
homelands," she said.
</P>
<P>
Talks between parties to the conflict in the DRC have slowed
since the July 10 accord was signed, with some rebel leaders
refusing to endorse the cease-fire and continuing their advance.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, fighting between government forces and rebels in
neighboring Congo (B) has been unrelenting since December 1998.
This month, the conflict pushed thousands of refugees into Gabon.
</P>
<P>
In Africa's Great Lakes region, the UNHCR has only 3.4 million
U.S. dollars available, which is enough to assist the region's
more than 750,000 refugees for only two more weeks.
</P>
<P>
In spite of the funding difficulties, the UNHCR has to
establish new camps in Tanzania, Gabon, and the Central African
Republic.
</P>
<P>
"Contributions are not even meeting the needs of long-time
refugees, much less the newest arrivals," Ogata warned.
</P>
<P>
In the east of the DRC, more than 600 refugees a day are
fleeing across Lake Tanganyika aboard small boats to escape
fighting between rebels and local opposition groups.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 100,000 Congolese refugees are now crowded into two
refugee sites in western Tanzania and aid workers fear a rise in
tension in the camps.
</P>
<P>
The war in the DRC, the third largest country in the continent,
has also compelled more than 14,000 Congolese to flee into remote
areas of the Central African Republic during the past few weeks.
</P>
<P>
More arrivals are expected from the town of Zongo and the UNHCR
is rushing aid to the remote region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
