<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Introduce Alcohol to Petrol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Petrol containing alcohol
will be introduced in South Africa next Monday, a statement
jointly made by South African petroleum industrial groups said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The blend, containing a maximum of 12 percent alcohol by
volume, would be distributed through the leaded 93-octane petrol
dispensing network in Gauteng province and parts of Mpumalanga,
said the statement made by South Africa's petrochemical giant,
Sasol, the South African Petroleum Industry Association, the
African Minerals and Energy Forum, and the National Association of
Automobile Manufacturers of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"Sasol confirms that it accepts responsibility for the quality
of the petrol/alcohol blend that it supplies," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Since the news of the alcohol-petrol was first made public, the
 Automobile Association (AA) has expressed reservations about the
product, saying an alcohol-blended petrol additive containing 65
percent ethanol had caused major problems with vehicles a few
years ago.
</P>
<P>
Sasol said extensive tests over the period of 18 months were
conducted in collaboration with all stake holders and on all
ranges of vehicles including imported ones. No problems were
identified.
</P>
<P>
The blended petrol would be sold at the standard price.
</P>
</TEXT>
