<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Farmers' Average Land Holding Decreases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The average land holding of
Ethiopian farmers had decreased from 1.8 hectares in 1988 to 0.8
hectares in 1998, a government official said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Bateno Kabeto, senior official of the Ethiopian Ministry of
Agriculture, told an expert meeting that the level of production
and productivity in the Horn of Africa country is far below to
meet even the minimum food security standard set by the United
Nations, which is 2,100 kilo calorie per day.
</P>
<P>
Bateno attributed the decrease of land holding to land
degradation and over population.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that future increase in food production must
come primarily from higher yields per unit area rather than from
expansion of land.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia, with a population of 62 million, is the third most
populous country in Africa next to Nigeria and Egypt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
