<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Chinese Killed in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 21 (Xinhua) -- An autopsy performed
Wednesday on three Chinese men found dead in a locked shop in
Senekal, about 300 km south of Johannesburg showed that all three
were shot in the head at close range, police said.
</P>
<P>
Captain Corlea Herholdt said two of the men were also stabbed
in the chest and neck.
</P>
<P>
The victims, whose bodies were found Tuesday, were named as Fa
Mai Ye, in his 50s, of Senekal, believed to be the owner of the
Family Fashions shop where the bodies were found, and Zhong Quang
Yang and Li Jiang who had came to the shop to help Fa before being
killed.
</P>
<P>
Police were called after two people looked through the shop
window and saw a body on the floor. There were no signs of forced
entry and the shop was locked when police arrived.
</P>
<P>
Herholdt said the motive for the killing appeared to have been
robbery as clothing and blankets were missing from the store.
</P>
<P>
Donald Wong, Chairman of the Chinese Association, said: "These
people are investing in the country to help the people of South
Africa."
</P>
<P>
"A lot of them are already contemplating leaving because of the
crime. It is not only the Chinese community that is affected, but
all members of South African society. The community and government
must work together to help police to curb crime," Wong said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
