<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA to Count-down Free Trade Area Set for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Common Market for East and
Southern Africa (COMESA) is launching various count-down
activities among its member states towards a free trade area
scheduled for October 31, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Jerome Ntibarekerwa, Director of Infrastructure Development of
the COMESA, told Xinhua in Lusaka Wednesday that the special
committee of ministers, which is comprising Kenya, Mauritius,
Zambia, Uganda, Egypt, Zimbabwe, Malawi and the Democratic
Republic of Congo (DRC), has agreed on a number of activities
which should be implemented as the count-down to the free trade
area.
</P>
<P>
These activities include: publication of COMESA Tariffs by
member states; organization of a COMESA Trade Fair during the
extraordinary summit in October 2000; governments to encourage
trade missions to partner member states from July 1999 and beyond;
public lectures at universities on the free trade area, investment
and trade opportunities.
</P>
<P>
Jerome noted that since the first meeting of the officials on
the count- down on the COMESA free trade area, which was held in
Lusaka on June 24, the member states have intensified their
efforts to eliminate non- tariff barriers and other obstacles to
trade.
</P>
<P>
Most member states have made good progress in removal of tariff
barriers.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June this year, four countries had published the
90 percent tariff reduction, six countries 80 percent, one country
70 percent and three countries 60 percent, Jerome said.
</P>
<P>
He said the objective of the count-down was to publicize the
COMESA as widely as possible so as to ensure that the regional
free trade area would be launched on the due date and to enable
the business community to take advantage of the opportunities
presented by the free trade area.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Jerome said that member states also committed
themselves to cooperate in the promotion of peace, security and
stability and to this end, the Special Committee of Ministers
attended the peace talks on the Democratic Republic of Congo held
earlier in Lusaka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
