<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Signing of E. African Community Treaty Might be </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The signing of a treaty for
the establishment of the East African Community might be postponed
for weeks, government sources said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Although no official announcements have been made to change the
set date for the signing of the document by the presidents of
Kenya, Tanzania and Uganda, the sources said experts from the
three countries are still holding consultations on a number of
standing issues, including trade tariffs.
</P>
<P>
The East African Community, aims to create a common market
between the three countries, to be followed by monetary union and
ultimately a political federation. The signing of the treaty was
originally set on July 30.
</P>
<P>
The community is to be formed on the basis of the current East
African Cooperation (EAC), which was set up by the three countries
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The highest decision making body of the East African
Cooperation, the Permanent Tripartite Commission, will converge
Friday in north Tanzania's Arusha town in an extraordinary meeting
to decide the date for the signing of the East African Community
treaty, among other issues.
</P>
<P>
According to EAC officials, the commission, made up of
ministers who are responsible for cooperation-related sectors,
will review the revised version of the draft treaty completed by
experts last week.
</P>
<P>
Before the three presidents put their signatures to the
document, the attorneys general of the partner states, are lined
up to give legal consideration to the treaty.
</P>
<P>
The Executive Secretary of the EAC, Francis Muthaura, said the
signing of the treaty depends on how fast the commission would
take to make suggestions on the revisited text.
</P>
<P>
"But it will be just a matter of time, a few days or weeks,
before the signing," he told reporters in Arusha Monday.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania and Uganda have expressed concern that the quick
reduction of a zero internal tariff and a common market tariff
would lead to a flood of products into their markets from Kenya,
which dominates trade in the region.
</P>
<P>
The former East African Community collapsed in 1977 because of
political and economic divergences. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
