<HEADLINE> Kuwaiti, Sudanese Ties to be Normalized: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 21 (Xinhua) -- A senior Kuwaiti official
hinted on Wednesday that Kuwait and Sudan will soon resume their
bilateral ties damaged by Khartoum's sympathy with Iraq during
the 1991 Gulf war.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese Foreign Minister will arrive here next Monday to
"hoist his country's flag on the Embassy" building, First Deputy
Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Sabah Al-Ahmad Al-Sabah told
reporters after attending a session of the Parliament's Foreign
Affairs Committee.
</P>
<P>
Sabah said bilateral relations between the two countries will
be back to normal "in favor of Kuwait."
</P>
<P>
Sudan will be the last so-called adversary state to restore
ties with Kuwait since the Gulf war triggered by Iraq's invasion
of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Since early March this year, foreign ministers of Jordan and
Yemen, also considered to be sympathized with Baghdad, had visited
Kuwait, bringing back to normal their damaged ties.
</P>
<P>
On Kuwait's relations with these countries, Sabah said there
was almost full agreement that "there is no permanent friend or
permanent enemy at the foreign policy level."
</P>
<P>
Expressing his own perspective, he said relations with these
states should be restored, particularly Jordan, irrespective of
the Jordanian government's stance during the Iraq aggression of
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
But he said it is still premature to embark on a tour to the
"adversary" states only if these visits serve the Kuwaiti causes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
