<HEADLINE> Clinton Assured Arafat on Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- United States President Bill Clinton
told Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat that Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak had promised to carry out all agreements signed with
the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
In his phone call to the Palestinian National Authority
chairman Wednesday, Clinton briefed Arafat on his recent talks
with Barak, who had concluded his six-day visit in Washington on
Tuesday, the Palestine Voice radio reported.
</P>
<P>
Barak's proposals for peace would be made "in complete good
faith," and any changes to previous Israeli-Palestinian agreements
would have to be made by mutual consent, Clinton told Arafat.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president pledged to make continued efforts to help
push ahead the peace process until a true and comprehensive peace
is achieved in the region, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Barak has suggested to wrap the U.S.-brokered Wye agreement,
frozen last December by his hard-line predecessor Benjamin
Netanyahu, into the final status talks.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians has rejected the proposal and demanded that
Israel immediately carry out the Wye accord, according to which
Israel should pull out from 13 percent of the West Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
