<HEADLINE> U.S., Vietnam Narrow Gap on Trade Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Negotiations between the United
States and Vietnam on establishing normal trade relations have
made significant progress, the State Department said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We have made significant progress in narrowing the number of
outstanding issues, but there are some issues that do remain,"
spokesman James Rubin told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"We do hope that these discussions will be sufficient to enable
us to conclude an agreement and will achieve the objectives," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The agreement the United States is seeking is to require
Vietnam to make commitments on market access for goods and
services, intellectual property and investment.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said the agreement once concluded would pave the way for
normalizing trade relations between the two countries. It also
would expedite Vietnam's entry into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese officials said last week that the two sides had
substantially narrowed their differences in an eighth round of
negotiations in Washington last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
