<HEADLINE> Schroeder Calls on SPD Party Members to Back </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 21 (Xinhua) -- German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder
on Wednesday sent a personal letter to the 800,000 members of his
Social Democratic Party (SPD), seeking their support on his
austerity reform.
</P>
<P>
The SPD members should "more offensively" advocate cabinet's
austerity policy, at work and at neighborhood, said the letter
publicized by the party's headquarters in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
Germans have "no alternative" to a sharp cut on their state
spending, or there won't be any job creation, it continued.
</P>
<P>
In his letter, Schroeder said he had taken over a highest state
debt of 1500 billion marks, a highest jobless rate, and a highest
tax rate from his predecessor, Helmut Kohl.
</P>
<P>
And today, Germans must pay one fourth of every mark they have
earned for interest of the debt, the letter said.
</P>
<P>
Last month, German Finance Minister Hans Weichel put forward a
major fiscal reform package, aiming to lower government's budget
by 1.5 per cent in year 2000 and more drastically cut corporate
tax rate.
</P>
<P>
Respective sparing will be made in jobless relief, public
healthy insurance, pension and other social welfares under the
pro-business package.
</P>
<P>
The reform plan, though backed by Schroeder and business
leaders, was widely hit by the left-wingers in the SPD. They said
Schroeder, who is also chairman of the party, had betrayed SPD's
traditional line of "social state".  
</P>
</TEXT>
