<HEADLINE> World Food Program to Donate Malawi $30M in Food </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program (WFP) said
Wednesday that it will give Malawi some 16.8 million U.S. dollars
worth of food aid, according to a report from Malawian capital
Lilongwe.
</P>
<P>
In line with an agreement signed early July by the WFP and the
Malawian government on food security upto the year 2001, the
agency will also donate some12.2 million dollars for supplementary
activities in the country's food security program, Felix Bamezone,
WFP representative in Malawi, was quoted as saying,
</P>
<P>
The agreement shall enable the WFP to provide 51,555 tons of
food through three basic activities like assistance to
malnourished groups, rural infrastructure rehabilitation and
development and human resource development through increased
primary education opportunities for girls, said Bamezone.
</P>
<P>
The supplementary activities include vulnerability assessment,
training and soya beans revolving fund, the WFP official added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Malawian President Bakili Muluzi has pledged his
government will work towards improving the livelihood of
Malawians, despite adverse condition.
</P>
<P>
Muluzi government wants to improve agriculture by providing
free fertilizer and seed to farming families.
</P>
<P>
Some 5,000 tons of fertilizer was already in the country and
25,000 tons more will be imported. 
</P>
