<HEADLINE> No Insurgents Against Burundi Trained in Tanzania: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The leader of Kagera Region
in northwest Tanzania has strongly refuted allegations that
insurgents were trained in the region to launch attacks against
the Burundian government.
</P>
<P>
Kagera Regional Commissioner Mohamed Babu said in Bukoba,
capital of Kagera, Wednesday that allegations made by the
Burundian government were baseless and unfounded.
</P>
<P>
Babu made it clear that Tanzania has abided by the
international law which does not allow refugees to engage in
political activities, reports from Kagera said.
</P>
<P>
The Tanzanian government has taken measures against hundreds of
illegal refugees in Kagera, he said.
</P>
<P>
At present, there are about 96,000 Burundian refugees living in
camps in the Ngara district of the region.
</P>
<P>
Recently, authorities in the region arrested over 200 Burundian
refugees who had escaped from Lukole, a camp in Ngara and were
later prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, seven men who were dressed like soldiers of
Rwandan Patriotic Front were arrested near the Rwanda border and
appropriate steps have been taken against them, Babu said.
</P>
<P>
He said all border districts of Burundi near the Tanzania side
have been peaceful except those bordering the Democratic Republic
of Congo.
</P>
<P>
Burundian President Pierre Buyoya was recently quoted by press
reports as saying that Burundi insurgents were under training in
Tanzania's border regions of Kagera and Kigoma, before launching
attacks against his government forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
