<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Markets Hit By Heavy Sell-Off On Wall St. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Europe's major stock markets closed
firmly in the red Wednesday owing to the previous session's heavy
sell-off on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
The UK's FTSE 100 fell almost 1 percent to finish at 6,239.8, a
drop of 62 points, with oil stocks contributing a large part of
the fall as the price of crude came under pressure for the second
day running.
</P>
<P>
Shares in BP Amoco, the UK's biggest company, ended down 41
pence, or 3.3 percent, at 1,190, while rival Shell was down 15.75
pence, or 3 percent, at 504 pence.
</P>
<P>
Provisional volume in London was again thin, with a shade under
1 billion shares changing hands.
</P>
<P>
Frankfurt's Xetra Dax endured the worst of the selling to end
down 1.4 percent, or 77 points, at 5,414.17.
</P>
<P>
Bank stocks led the way lower, although a strengthening euro
also unnerved investors worried that it could slow the
export-driven economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
France's CAC 40 suffered a 1 percent drop to close at 4,501.27,
a fall of 47 points, in a very quiet session. The start of the
European holiday season is partly to blame. 
</P>
</TEXT>
