<HEADLINE> Nigerian Speaker Steps Aside Temporarily </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABUJA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria's House of Representatives
remained in confusion Wednesday over allegations of age and
certificate forgeries against Speaker Ibrahim Buhari.
</P>
<P>
The speaker has decided to step aside to allow for full
investigations into the allegations made by The News magazine on
July 11.
</P>
<P>
But his apparent supporters prevented the house from debating a
motion on the allegation, forcing his deputy Chibudom Nwuche to
adjourn Wednesday session.
</P>
<P>
At the resumed session Wednesday, Nwuche read a letter from
Buhari restating his decision to step down as speaker so that the
house could debate the motion on the forgery allegation against
him.
</P>
<P>
The working committee of the ruling People's Democratic Party
(PDP), to which Speaker Buhari belongs, has asked him to stand
aside to allow for a thorough investigation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Nigeria's Senate, the Upper House of the 469-member
National Assembly, has referred the Buhari case to its committees
on ethnics, judiciary, security and intelligence.
</P>
<P>
Supporters of Buhari say that the speaker is innocent until
proved guilty, and the issue should be allowed to go through the
courts.
</P>
<P>
The magazine alleged that Speaker Buhari lied about his age and
 qualifications in order to secure his position, which ranks
fourth in Nigeria's constitutional hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
The magazine said that he was only 29 year old but he claimed
to be 36 so as be qualified for the speaker's post which is
demanded by the country' s constitution.  
</P>
</TEXT>
