<HEADLINE> West African Peace-keeping Force Gets New </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Brig. Gen. Gabriel Kpemba
has been appointed as the new commander of the west African
peace-keeping force ECOMOG in Sierra Leone, a report reaching here
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The former directorate of operations at the Nigerian Army
Headquarters replaces Maj. Gen. Felix Mujakpero who has been
ECOMOG commander for six months.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement by the defense headquarters in Lagos,
the change in ECOMOG command is part of a major re-deployment of
some 191 top military officers.
</P>
<P>
Mujakpero is to head the directorate of training and doctrine
command of the Nigerian army.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, it was reported that Nigeria will begin to withdraw
its troops from Sierra Leone from August 26 this year.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Information Minister Dapo Sarumi was quoted as saying
that a date for the withdrawal from the Nigerian-dominated force,
which had backed Sierra Leonean President Ahmad Tejan Kabbah
against his former rebel foes, was set during Wednesday's cabinet
meeting presided over by President Olusegun Obasanjo.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria, which has the largest contingent in the 10,000-strong
regional force, announced it would begin a phased withdrawal of
its troops from the war-ravaged west African country after the
Sierra Leone government and rebels signed a peace agreement
earlier this month to end over eight years of civil war.
</P>
<P>
With the peace deal, Nigeria also said its mandate had changed
from defending Kabbah's government to disarmament and
rehabilitation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
