<HEADLINE> New Refugees Pour Across Central African Borders: U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- More than 50,000 people
have been forced to flee the Democratic Republic of the Congo
(DRC) and Congo-Brazzaville over the past three weeks, the United
Nations reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Half of these new refugees have fled fighting in the east and
north of the DRC where the conflict continues despite a peace
agreement signed in Lusaka, Zambia, on July 10, a U.N. spokesman
quoted the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) as saying.
</P>
<P>
High Commissioner Sadako Ogata said political solutions must be
found urgently for the crises in the area, warning that
contributions to help refugees in the Great Lakes are "not even
meeting the needs of long-time refugees, much less than new
arrivals".
</P>
<P>
According to UNHCR, talks between parties to the conflict in
the DRC have slowed since the July 10 accord, with some rebel
leaders refusing to endorse the cease-fire deal and continuing
their advance.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, fighting between government forces and rebels
in neighboring Congo-Brazzaville has been unrelenting since
December 1998, with thousands of refugees fleeing into another
neighboring country, Gabon.  
</P>
</TEXT>
