<HEADLINE> Voter Registration In East Timor Moves Peacefully: U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Voter registration for the
popular consultation in East Timor has proceeded peacefully, U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
There have been no further incidents in which staff or property
of the United Nations Mission in East Timor (UNMET) have been
attacked or seriously threatened in the first few days of
registration, he said in his latest report on UNAMET.
</P>
<P>
UNAMET was set up according to an agreement between Indonesia
and Portugal. It has the mandate to organize and conduct a vote to
determine the future of the disputed territory between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, situated north of Australia, was a Portuguese
colony until 1975 when a civil rift led Indonesia to occupy and
annex it in 1976.
</P>
<P>
Since then the United Nations has been seeking a solution to
the issue while regarding it as a non-self-governing territory.
</P>
<P>
The voting date was set for late August, with voter
registration starting on July 16. Those aged above 17 among the
territory's 800,000 inhabitants are eligible to choose wide-range
autonomy within Indonesia or independence of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Annan said the Indonesian authorities have made serious efforts
to provide the necessary security conditions.
</P>
<P>
He said a large number of East Timorese are internally
displaced and UNAMET is developing plans to help them take part
in the voting process.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
