<HEADLINE> Former New Zealand PM Gets WTO's Job in Compromise Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Former New Zealand prime
minister Mike Moore is expected to become the next
director-general of the World Trade Organization (WTO) Thursday
night (New Zealand time) when the organization officially endorses
the appointment.
</P>
<P>
Moore and Thai Deputy Prime Minister Supachai Panitchpakdi had
been locked in a battle for the coveted position, with neither
prepared to give up.
</P>
<P>
After months of bitter wrangling, an informal meeting of the
WTO's ruling general council has agreed to a compromise under
which the two candidates will split the six-year term with Moore
serving the first three years from September 1 and Supachai taking
over the post for the remaining three years.
</P>
<P>
Born in 1949, Moore joined the New Zealand Labor Party when he
was 17 years old. He entered the Parliament first as Labor MP in
1972. Since then he has been serving in the Parliament with only a
three-year interruption. In Labor governments, Moore held a range
of offices including minister of Overseas Trade and Marketing,
minister of Tourism, Sport and Recreation, minister in charge of
Publicity, and minister of Foreign Affairs.
</P>
<P>
He was once the prime minister for less than two months in
1990.
</P>
<P>
Moore had been a worker before he began his political life. He
advocates free trade and is the author of a number of
publications.
</P>
<P>
He is married to Yvonne and they have no children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
