<HEADLINE> N. Irish Pact Produces No Tangible Progress: IRA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Irish Republican Army said
Wednesday that Northern Ireland's 15-month-old Good Friday peace
accord had not delivered tangible progress and it blamed the
British government for the province's political crisis.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to An Phoblact, weekly organ of the IRA's Sinn
Fein political wing, the IRA said current demands for guerrilla
disarmament reflected "the failed agenda which seeks the defeat of
the IRA."
</P>
<P>
"The British government have the power to change that
(political) context and should do so," the IRA was quoted by a
Reuters report filed from Belfast as saying.
</P>
<P>
The guerrilla group said that over the past five years it had
maintained two lengthy cease-fires to "enhance the peace process
and underline our definitive commitment to its success."
</P>
<P>
The statement was the first by the IRA since the 1998 Good
Friday peace deal, signed by Sinn Fein and pro-British Unionist
politicians, was hit by a crisis last week.
</P>
<P>
The Protestant Unionists rejected plans to set up a coalition
provincial government in the British province before the IRA
disarmed. In recent weeks politicians in Britain and the Irish
Republic have urged the IRA to make a statement committing itself
to disarmament and to declare that its war against British rule in
the province was over. 
</P>
