<HEADLINE> Barak Says Time Right For Israel to Make Peace with Arabs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak
said here Wednesday that the time was right for his country to
achieve peace with all its Arab neighbors.
</P>
<P>
Barak, speaking after holding talks with British Prime Minister
Tony Blair, said he had appreciated the "positive signs" from
Syria since he took office earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
"I do highly appreciate the positive signals that are reaching
us and the external world from Syria," Barak told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"I think the time is right for achieving a peace of the brave
between Israel and all its neighbors including Syria.... Time is
of the essence for the whole process. We cannot sit idly and wait
for the whole process to be solved somehow," Barak said.
</P>
<P>
Asked about his hopes of major progress towards a comprehensive
Middle East peace within 15 months, he said it should not be too
rigid a time frame.
</P>
<P>
"I won't ask for a medal if it takes nine months, but nor will
I jump from a tower if it takes 24," said the new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Barak told Blair that Britain and its partners in the
European Union could play a key role in reviving the peace process
in the Middle East, both politically and financially.
</P>
<P>
The role of Europe, with Great Britain as a central player,
would create an atmosphere of support for peace efforts, both
politically and financially, Barak said.
</P>
<P>
Barak also outlined his peace plans to Blair during a stop-off
in London on his way home following a six-day trip to the United
States. 
</P>
