<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia, Eritrea Urged to Sign Modalities Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Security
Council Wednesday urged Ethiopia and Eritrea to formally sign the
modalities put forward by the Organization of African Unity (OAU)
for the implementation of a framework agreement.
</P>
<P>
Both Horn of Africa countries, which have been at war over
disputed frontier territories since May 6, 1998, said they have
accepted the terms of the OAU framework on the settlement of their
border conflict.
</P>
<P>
The modalities, adopted by a three-day OAU summit which ended
Last Wednesday in Algiers, provide that Eritrea commit itself to
redeploy its forces outside the territories they occupied after
May 6, 1998.
</P>
<P>
While Ethiopia is obliged to commit itself to redeploy its
forces from positions taken after February 6, 1999 and which were
not under Ethiopian administration before May 6, 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council said its members welcomed the initial
positive responses by both parties to the modalities.
</P>
<P>
The council made the statement after hearing a briefing by
Mohamed Sahnoun, special envoy of U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan.
</P>
<P>
Council members commended the efforts of concerned
international organizations, countries and individuals "to secure
this agreement and expressed their hope that this proves to be an
important step towards the resolution of this devastating
conflict," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Members of the Council expressed their readiness to support
the OAU in the implementation of the framework agreement once the
modalities have been signed," it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
