<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Gov't Committed to Ensuring Rights of Children </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina on Thursday said that her government has been making
all-out efforts for development and welfare of children in the
country.
</P>
<P>
She made the remarks while formally launching the "Progress of
Nations 1999", an annual UNICEF publication, here in Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
The annual UNICEF publication monitors global advances made
towards achieving the goals set at the 1990 World Summit for
Children, which documents the enormous steps that have been taken
globally towards the eradication of polio, in synergy with the
initiative to eliminate vitamin A deficiency.
</P>
<P>
"Our aim is to ensure education, nursing, food and medical-care
to the children," she said.
</P>
<P>
The government constituted the National Children Council in
1996, which has been working for formulating policy and ensuring
welfare for the protection of rights and interests of children,
she added.
</P>
<P>
A project titled "Coordinated program for Prevention of Child
Trafficking from Bangladesh" has been taken up, she further said.
"I declared the decade from 2001 to 2010 as the decade of
children's rights with a view to achieving children's rights."
</P>
<P>
Hasina stressed the need for children education, saying that
her government has formed the National Primary and Mass Education
Council, and the Education policy Committee has already submitted
its report to the government.
</P>
<P>
"Our government has been continuing the relentless efforts to
free new born babies from six diseases," she said, adding "We have
strengthened the social movement to increase consciousness about
breast-feeding of the child." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
