<HEADLINE> India, Namibia Sign Two Agreements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 22 (Xinhua) -- India and Namibia Thursday
signed two agreements including one on extending five million U.S.
dollar Exim Bank line of credit to the African country.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Namibian President Sam Nujoma, who arrived here
Wednesday for a three-day state visit, held wide-ranging
discussions with Indian caretaker Prime Minister Atal Behari
Vajpayee Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also signed a Memorandum of Understanding on
cooperation in non-conventional energy resources.
</P>
<P>
Namibia showed interest in acquiring from India, among other
things, maritime vessels and helicopters, a senior official of the
External Affairs Ministry said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
India's Central Electronics Ltd will set up a manufacturing
unit for solar panels and modules in Namibia which would help the
African country promote the use of solar energy, according to the
Press Trust of India (PTI).
</P>
<P>
The Namibian leader also held a separate meeting with External
Affairs Minister Jaswant Singh Wednesday and discussed issues of
international, regional and mutual concern.
</P>
<P>
Namibia has been keen on enhancing cooperation with India in
areas relating to human resource development, various facets of
agriculture and also for setting up industries, including joint
venture, in its export-processing zone, official sources said.
</P>
<P>
India and Namibia enjoy traditional close and warm relations
with India among the first countries to recognize the ruling
South-West African People's Organization as the sole
representative of the Namibian people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
