<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annual Inflation Down in Euro Zone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The annual inflation fell
slightly between May and June in the 11-nation euro zone, Eurostat
reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The statistical bureau of the European communities said in a
report that the inflation rate fell from 1.0 percent to 0.9
percent in the mentioned period.
</P>
<P>
A year earlier the rate was 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The highest inflation rate was found in Spain, Ireland, the
Netherlands and Portugal all with 2.1 percent while the lowest
inflation rate was found in Austria with 0.2 percent. Germany,
France and Sweden had the next lowest inflation rates at 0.4
percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Eurostat gave a comparison of 2.0 percent of inflation for the
United States and 0.6 percent for Switzerland. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Predicts More Cereal Imports by Afghanistan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Predicting 16 percent reduction
in this year's cereal production in Afghanistan, a recent U.N.
survey said the war-ravaged country is expected to import more
cereals, said U.N. sources here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Food and Agriculture Organization and the World Food
Program of the United Nations conducted a joint Crop and Food
Supply Assessment to Afghanistan in June this year to estimate the
1999 cereal harvest and subsequent cereal import requirements for
1999-2000.
</P>
<P>
Results of the assessment indicate that total cereal production
for 1999 will be about 16 percent below that of last year, said
the sources.
</P>
<P>
Afghanistan needs to import at least 1.1 million tons of
cereals to meet the food requirements for the year 1999-2000, but
there is expected to be a shortfall of over 200,000 tons,
according the assessment report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
