<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commission in Favor of Britain's Partial Schengen Request </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission announced
its favorable opinion Thursday on the British request to partially
participate in the Schengen treaty.
</P>
<P>
The executive body of the 15-nation bloc said that the partial
participation related to police and judicial cooperation in
criminal matters, to narcotic drugs and to the Schengen
Information System.
</P>
<P>
The commission believed that the proposed cooperation should in
due course be extended to the aspects of freedom of movement
covered by the Schengen Convention.
</P>
<P>
The Schengen Convention provides for the abolition of checks on
individuals at internal frontiers, plus accompanying measures to
guarantee the security of the citizens of signatory states of the
European Union, including checks at external frontiers, visas,
freedom of movement for third-country citizens, measures to combat
illegal immigration, drugs, and an information exchange system.
</P>
<P>
The convention was signed on June 19, 1990, by France, Germany,
Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg. All EU member states
except for Britain and Ireland have since signed the treaty.
</P>
<P>
The Schengen treaty was incorporated into the framework of the
EU with the coming into force of the Treaty of Amsterdam on May 1
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
