<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spanish PM Delivers Message From Assad to Barak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Spanish Prime Minister
Jose Maria Aznar delivered a message from Syrian President Hafez
al-Assad to Prime Minister Ehud Barak Thursday on the resumption
of Israeli-Syrian talks.
</P>
<P>
Aznar declined to reveal the details of the message but he told
reporters after his meeting with Barak that he is optimistic about
the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by Barak's office said Aznar briefed Barak on
his recent talks with Syrian, Lebanese, Jordanian and Palestinian
leaders during his five-day Middle East tour. Israel is the last
stop of his trip.
</P>
<P>
In their talks, Barak outlined his ideas for advancing the
stalled peace process, both on the Palestinian and Syrian tracks,
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Barak noted that good intentions by both parties, cooperation,
and discussions on issues as partners will enable a breakthrough
in solving the century-old conflict in the Middle East," it said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy told Israel's Army
Radio that Aznar told him that Assad does not want to waste an
opportunity to make peace with Israel's new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Ousting hard-line Benjamin Netanyahu in the prime ministerial
election in May, Barak has pledged to push forward the peace
process with Syria as well as the Palestinians, which was largely
frozen in the last three years.
</P>
<P>
He promised to resume the peace talks with Damascus under the
framework of United Nations Resolutions 242 and 338, which call
for Israel to relinquish Arab land it occupied in the 1967 Middle
East war, including the strategic plateau of Golan Heights of
Syria.
</P>
<P>
Since his election victory, Barak has traded compliments and
trust-building signals with Assad, the former arch-foe in the
battlefield.
</P>
<P>
There have been reports that Damascus has asked radical
Palestinian groups based in Syria to stop armed struggle against
Israel. Barak welcomed the reports.
</P>
<P>
Israel's army chief admitted Wednesday that Syria is also
taking action to restrain Hezbollah guerrillas, who are fighting
to oust Israel from its occupation zone in southern Lebanon, from
firing Katyusha rockets into northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
On the Palestinian track, Barak briefed his Spanish counterpart
on his proposal to combine the implementation of the Wye River
Memorandum with the final status talks "in a way that would
increase the chances of reaching the permanent settlement with the
Palestinians and strengthen security," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian National Authority has rejected Barak's
proposal, calling for the immediate implementation of the interim
agreement, which was signed and then frozen by Netanyahu last
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
