<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Forex Market Hit by Shortfalls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's foreign exchange market
which has seen improved inflows from tobacco was hit by serious
shortfalls during the week ended July 21, said the Reserve Bank of
Zimbabwe Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The bank said in its weekly foreign exchange report released
here Thursday that the market which has been hit by shortages for
the greatest part of the past two months, nose-dived during the
past week from a deficit of one million U.S. dollars on July 15 to
a deficit of 4.8 million U.S. dollars Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said foreign exchange inflows stood at 95
million U.S. dollars while outflows were at 99.3 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The market ended the week with a surplus of 3.3 million U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
The past week recorded the highest inflows of 51.1 million U.S.
dollars on July 19 with the highest outflows on the same day at
48.9 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
On the currency front, the Zimbabwe dollar lost against the
greenback trading at 38.1 Zimbabwean dollars as against 37.9 in
the past fortnight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
