<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment Surges in Fujian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Fujian, a coastal province in south
China, reported rise in overseas investment in the first six
months this year, absorbing contracted overseas funds totaling 2,
613 million U.S. dollars, or an increase of 3.8 percent over the
figure for the same 1998 period.
</P>
<P>
According to local officials, the province has taken a series
of measures to encourage overseas investment since the beginning
of this year, which have paid off.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investments from European countries, the United States
and Southeast Asian countries, as well as from Hong Kong and
Taiwan regions have all reported steady rises.
</P>
<P>
From January to June, overseas funds which arrived in the
province topped 2,327 million U.S. dollars, representing a rise of
4.4 percent over the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
Major cities in the province, except Xiamen, one of the country
's key special economic zones, approved an additional 91 overseas-
funded projects in the first half year.
</P>
<P>
From January to June this year, some 525 overseas-funded
projects in the province witnessed increases in overseas
investment, fully showing the confidence of investors in
developing Chinese markets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
