<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysian FM on Foreign Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Malaysian Foreign Minister
Syed Hamid Albar said Thursday the country's high priority is that
while developing close bilateral relations with its neighbors, it
would continue to adhere to the policy of non-interference in
internal affairs of other countries.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the remarks in his address on "Malaysia's
Foreign Policy" at a forum on strategic issues organized by the
Asian Strategy and Leadership Institute here.
</P>
<P>
Syed Hamid was of the view that globalization and information
technology would impact strongly on Malaysia's foreign policy in
the next millennium.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia would continue to push for the strengthening of ASEAN
(Association of Southeast Asian Nations) as a regional grouping.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that despite criticisms made against ASEAN,
it's clear that cooperation within ASEAN is now firmly entrenched
and ASEAN is not about to lose its dynamism, viability and
relevance with the inclusion of new member states.
</P>
<P>
On the relations between Malaysia and Singapore, he said both
countries should move out of the old mould and mature into what
their ties ought to be -- interdependent, proximate and mutually
beneficial.
</P>
<P>
He said relations between Malaysia and Singapore should be
premised on a "win-win formula" endorsed by their citizens.
</P>
<P>
On the occasion, Syed Hamid reiterated Malaysia's "one-China
policy."
</P>
<P>
On the relations with the West, he said there was no
contradiction between Malaysia's justifiable criticisms of the
West on certain issues and its continued acceptance of Western
countries as a market for the country's products and as a source
of investment.
</P>
<P>
He said that while continuing pursuing relations with
traditional economic partners such as Japan, the European Union,
Australia, South Korea as well as other countries, Malaysia would
only consider beginning relations with Israel upon successful
conclusion of a comprehensive peace agreement between Israel and
Palestine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
