<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Money Growth Increases Inflation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe
Thursday said high levels of money growth remain a major threat to
efforts to bring down inflation to levels consistent with
macro-economic activity.
</P>
<P>
The bank said in its weekly economic highlights for July 16
that the current high levels of money supply growth were
inconsistent with the economy's growth and inflation objectives.
</P>
<P>
According to the bank, money supply growth year-on-year
remained high during the first half of 1999, rising from 17
percent in January to 29.3 percent in March and 51.8 percent by
May.
</P>
<P>
"Price stability remains the main task and priority of monetary
policy. The major challenge facing the economy is the all time
high level of inflation, currently at 55.2 percent," it said.
</P>
<P>
"This requires the Reserve Bank to persist with a relatively
restrictive monetary policy in order to bring down inflation,
restore external viability and provide a sustainable basis for a
rebound in economic growth in an environment of low interest
rates," it said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said the high level of monetary growth in May required
it to maintain a tight monetary policy stance if inflation was to
be brought under control.
</P>
<P>
"High production costs across all sectors, including wage
adjustments have tended to generate a self propelling cost-push
inflation spiral," the central bank said.
</P>
<P>
To compliment its tight monetary policy, other measures to
resolve supply constraints would need to be implemented, it said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
