<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Ruling Body Appoints Two Consecutive Director-Generals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The ruling General Council of the
World Trade Organization (WTO) decided here Thursday to appoint
Mike Moore of New Zealand and Supachai Panithpakdi of Thailand as
the WTO's next two consecutive leaders, WTO spokesman Keith
Rockwell announced.
</P>
<P>
According to the formal decision, Moore is appointed as
Director-General for three years from September 1, 1999 to August
31,2002. Supachai will succeed Moore from September 1, 2002 for
three years to August 31, 2005.
</P>
<P>
WTO members agreed that neither should be eligible for re-
appointment as WTO Director-General, nor should his period of
office be extended.
</P>
<P>
It was also agreed that in March 2002, the General Council
shall re-confirm the availability of Supachai for office and if
Supachai is not available, the next WTO Director-General will be
from a developing country, General Council Chairman Ali Mchumo
told reporters at the end of the closed-door meeting.
</P>
<P>
Normally, the term of office of the WTO chief is four years
like former WTO Director-General Renato Ruggiero has served.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
