<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0136 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Continue Active Fiscal Policy (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- China may continue an active
fiscal policy in the next few years, Chinese economists predicted
today.
</P>
<P>
Mi Jianguo, director of the Macro-Economic Research Department
of the Development Research Center of the State Council, said that
an active policy based on increasing public debt and deficits will
be the top choice for the government to stimulate economic growth
over a relatively long period of time.
</P>
<P>
He noted that since effective demand is quite inadequate at
present, and private investment and consumption cannot be
kickstarted over the next one or two years, the Chinese government
has very few macro-economic policy choices.
</P>
<P>
"We should review the idea that fiscal policies are short-term
ones and cannot be used over a long time," he said.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Finance Xiang Huaicheng announced at a national
meeting on finance work held here today that China will adopt a
series of "powerful macro-economic policies" in the second half of
the year, including greatly increasing the issuance of treasury
bonds, boosting subsidies for low-income people and readjusting
tax policy.
</P>
<P>
China increased the issuance of treasury bonds by 100 billion
yuan-worth to fund infrastructure construction last year, adding 1.
5 percentage points to the economic growth rate.
</P>
<P>
However, since March, China has seen a rapid decrease in
exports and foreign investment due to intensified competition from
other Asia economies that are recovering from the financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
By the end of June, the growth rate of the country's investment
in fixed assets fell by one-half over the end of last December,
and the retail price index went down to score the 21st consecutive
monthly fall. Private consumption and investment have seen slower
growth rates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
