<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Continue Active Fiscal Policy (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Xiang warned today that if effective measures are not taken
promptly, the momentum of economic rebound that emerged in the
second half of last year will disappear and the growth of economy
may see a downward trend.
</P>
<P>
Mi noted that the Chinese economy is now at a historical stage
of changing from shortage to surplus, and the lagging behind of
micro-economic restructuring has effectively reduced the
effectiveness of macro-economic policies.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said that the government has to further step up
the dimension of the active fiscal policy in order to secure a
rapid economic growth rate, which in turn will give more time and
room for maneuver to economic restructuring.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that there is still plenty of room for adopting
a more active fiscal policy both on the demand and supply sides,
noting that Chinese banks now have a deposit-loan surplus of more
than 1,000 billion yuan, and infrastructure construction and
upgrading of state-owned enterprises need a great deal of funds.
He said that this room for maneuver will not disappear in the
short term.
</P>
<P>
Renowned Chinese economist Wu Jinglian said in an article that
since public debts account for less than ten percent of the
country's gross domestic product (GDP), China will be safe from
any serious financial risk for the next two or three years if it
increases the issuance of treasury bonds by some 100 billion yuan
every year.
</P>
<P>
Mi noted that the government has readjusted the way it uses the
money from issuing T-bonds so as to promote economic growth from
various aspects.
</P>
<P>
He said that further increasing public spending on
infrastructure construction will push ahead the production of
relevant industries and have a delayed effect on economic growth
in the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
