<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Step Up Active Fiscal Policy: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Minister of Finance Xiang
Huaicheng said here today that China will take more powerful
measures to implement its active fiscal policy in the second half
of the year in a bid to promote a sustained, steady development of
the national economy.
</P>
<P>
He told a national meeting on finance work that the government
is planning to increase the issuance of treasury bonds, raise
subsidies for low-income people and adjust tax policies in the
next six months.
</P>
<P>
Compared with last year, the minister said, these measures
meant for the next half this year include increasing investments
and consumption, supporting exports and adjusting tax policies,
which will be taken at the same time.
</P>
<P>
The implementation of these measures will lead to an increase
in the budget deficit and greater expenditure at local governments
as well, he cautioned.
</P>
<P>
He noted that in the first half of the year the Chinese
government had a fiscal revenue of 529.4 billion yuan, an increase
of 24.3 percent from a year earlier, and a fiscal expenditure of
464.8 billion yuan, up 16 percent, with a surplus of 64.6 billion
yuan, 39.7 billion yuan more than in the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The minister also called on financial departments to support
the reforms of state-owned enterprises and help them establish a
scientific and rational system for their assets supervision and
management.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
