<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pak, Iran to Enhance Measures to Control Drug Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan and Iran Thursday
reached an agreement to further their measures to check drug
smuggling in border areas.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached at the meeting held here between
Pakistan's Interior Minister Chaudhry Shujaat Hussain and a
visiting six-member Iranian delegation led by Muhammad Hossain
Zadeh, secretary of Iran's Drug Control Headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The two sides held detailed discussions on matters relating to
drug control program. They were also joined by technical experts
at the meeting identifying ways and means to control menace of
drugs, official sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian delegation was briefed on the steps being taken by
the Pakistani government to reduce poppy cultivation in border
areas with Afghanistan and curb drug smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Shujaat said both Pakistan and Iran have set up 52 check posts
to control drug smuggling on the Pak-Iran border.
</P>
<P>
All the check posts have started functioning which were
completed with the funds, provided by the United Nations Drug
Control Program (UNDCP), according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
The staff of these check posts are not only well trained but
also well equipped with modern communication systems including
latest wireless sets, he added.
</P>
<P>
According to an agreement with UNDCP signed in April this year,
UNDCP will provide a grant of 5.25 million rupees (about 110,000
U.S. dollars) for strengthening drug law enforcement agencies,
Shujaat said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
