<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Government Committed to Market Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government
emphasized Thursday that July 30 would be the deadline for an
agreement on the proposed merger of the Stock Exchange of Hong
Kong and the Hong Kong Futures Exchange and their associated
clearing houses.
</P>
<P>
If the two exchanges could not reach a merger agreement by then,
the government would be duty-bound to proceed immediately with the
reform through other means to make the securities market fully
competitive in a globalized setting of the next century, Donald
Tsang, financial secretary of the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR), said at a meeting with chairmen of the two exchanges.
</P>
<P>
The market reform was introduced by the financial secretary in
his budget speech in March.
</P>
<P>
The reform package includes reforming the market environment in
terms of market access for intermediaries and the levy and
commission structure, restructuring the governance of the
exchanges and clearing houses, rationalizing the market regulatory
functions and opening up the markets for more competition.
</P>
<P>
"We will mobilize all possible means at our disposal to
implement these objectives as quickly as possible," Tsang said.
</P>
<P>
The financial secretary also pledged that the government would
work further toward the opening up of the cash and futures markets
in Hong Kong to enhance competition.
</P>
<P>
"Much is at stake in our mission to be the Asian premier center
for international finance. And the window of reform is narrow," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the merger and listing proposal would yield
the most winners as it would give existing members of the
exchanges a unique opportunity to reap substantial benefits.
</P>
<P>
"We believe the demutualization and merger of the exchanges
under a commercial deal will benefit all parties concerned
including the brokers, the exchanges, market users, investors as
well as the public at large," said Tsang. 
</P>
</TEXT>
