<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Government Plans to Enact Transactions Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) government plans to enact the
Electronic Transaction Bill by the end of the year so as to
provide a favorable environment for electronic commerce to
flourish in the region.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a gathering of the Association of Engineers in
Society Thursday evening, Secretary for Information Technology and
Broadcasting K. C. Kwong said the bill sought to establish a clear
legal framework to enhance certainty and security in the conduct
of electronic transactions.
</P>
<P>
"When enacted, the bill will provide legal recognition to
electronic records and digital signatures in electronic
transactions in the same way as the legal recognition given to
their paper-based counterparts," Kwong said, adding that "It will
also provide a framework to facilitate and promote the operation
of certification authorities."
</P>
<P>
To provide a secure and trusted environment for the conduct of
electronic transactions, the government will take the lead and
will, through the Hong Kong Post, provide public certification
services to individuals as well as businesses by the end of this
year.
</P>
<P>
Other bodies in the private sector may also establish
certification authorities to serve the needs of the community.
</P>
<P>
"With the use of public and private key encryption mechanism,
digital signatures and the issue of digital certificates by
certification authorities, we will be able to verify the identity
of the counter parties to electronic transactions, ensure that the
integrity and confidentiality of messages exchanged in the
transactions would not be compromised, and safeguard against
repudiation after transactions are made," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central China Resisting Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, July 22 (Xinhua) -- More than 1.3 million soldiers and
civilians in the central China provinces of Hunan and Hubei have
been organized to battle the surging floodwater in the Yangtze
River.
</P>
<P>
In Hubei alone, which sits on the middle reaches of the country
's longest river, 340,000 soldiers and civilians are patrolling
the lengthy dikes built along the Yangtze to make sure that the
third flood peak on the river, also the largest this year, can
pass without causing any serious mishaps.
</P>
<P>
The third flood peak formed July 14 when the Yangtze valley was
hit by intensive rainfall, and flood waters are pressing
downstream to this capital of Hubei, after passing the Jingjiang
section, which is most vulnerable to dyke breaches because of its
zigzagging and narrow river courses, Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In Yueyang, a city on the southern bank of the Yangtze, 300,000
soldiers and civilians have been busy solidifying the main
embankments and building 174 km of new dikes to confront the flood
peak impending. Meanwhile, more than 350,000 people living in the
vicinity of dangerous dikes have been evacuated to safe ground by
local governments at various levels in the city.
</P>
<P>
Some 25,000 local people have been formed into a special team
to deal with possible emergencies in areas around Dongting Lake,
where the water level has been rising at a speed of one centimeter
per hour due to the surging floodwater in the mainstream of the
Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
Chenglingji Hydrology Station, located where Dongting Lake
joins the Yangtze, recorded a water level of 35.5 meters at 20:00
hours Wednesday, and is expected to reach 35.7 meters or even 35.
94 meters, a historical record, today.
</P>
<P>
There are altogether one million people in the lake area
patrolling the dikes and embankments and repairing cave-ins daily.
They include 10,000 soldiers drafted from outside Hunan to help
fight floods.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
