<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Combats Deadly Forest Diseases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHENGZHOU, July 22 (Xinhua) -- China's forestry authorities
Wednesday ordered an urgent mobilization against the American
white moths and pine wood nematode, which have caused severe
damage to forests in several Chinese provinces.
</P>
<P>
According to a conference held here by the State Forestry
Administration, American white moths have infested 28,900 ha of
forests around Tianjin City and in Hebei Province, while the pine
wood nematode has spread to 72,400 ha of forests in Jiangsu, Anhui,
Shandong, Zhejiang and Guangdong provinces, killing nearly 15
million pine trees.
</P>
<P>
The American white moth multiplies very rapidly and can spread
in many ways, hence posing a severe threat to forests, while the
pine wood nematode can kill huge numbers of pine trees in a very
short time, for which it is known as "pine wood cancer", experts
said.
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier Wen Jiabao has said that strong measures must be
taken to stop the spread of the deadly pests as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The conference concluded that urgent measures would be taken in
the said provinces to bring the situation under control and
eventually wipe out the diseases.
</P>
<P>
Measures recommended by the conference include the sealing-off
of the affected areas, establishing an effective monitoring system
and the combined use of chemical, physical and biological means.
</P>
<P>
The conference decided that Beijing would also take action to
bar the depredations of the American white moth.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Join ASEAN in Opening Farm Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has agreed with other
member countries of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations
(ASEAN) to continue liberalizing the agricultural sector, a senior
Commerce Ministry official said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Thavachai Sophasathianpong, deputy director-general of the
Department of Business Economics, said that Thailand and other
ASEAN members had agreed that the public and private sectors also
cooperate to formulate a common policy and stance at the World
Trade Organization's new round of multilateral trade talks, to be
started in Seattle in November.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN members also agreed that the common policy and stance be
based on three aspects, including continual liberalization of
agricultural products, ending of local subsidies and ending of
export subsidies, he said.
</P>
<P>
The continual liberalization of the farm sector involves
reduction of import tariffs on agricultural products, both with
and without agreed quota frameworks.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN members agreed in principle that they cut local subsidies
with a rate higher than that required by WTO's Uruguay Round of
trade talks, but more discussions were needed to finalize a common
rate of subsidies, said Thavachai.
</P>
<P>
In case of export subsidies, Thailand would not be obliged by
the issue as the country had never introduced any export subsidies
so far, he said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN now groups Brunei, Cambodia, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia,
Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Secretary-General Urges Regional Integration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 22 (Xinhua) -- ASEAN Secretary-General Rodolfo
Severino Thursday urged member countries to fulfill their
commitment to greater regional integration, which he said is
"inevitable."
</P>
<P>
In a report to the two-day ASEAN Ministerial Meeting (AMM)
which opens here on Friday, Severino said economic globalization
has brought about profound implications for regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Economic interdependence has reached a stage where developments
in some countries have profound implications for the rest of the
region, he said in the report, which was released on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Regional integration is inevitable and essential," the report
said. "ASEAN (the Association of Southeast Asian Nations) member
countries should not backtrack on their commitment to greater
regional integration."
</P>
<P>
"There is no alternative to regional cooperation and
integration. Globalization compels ASEAN member countries to
establish common positions on global issues and to take advantage
of its collective weight," the report said.
</P>
<P>
"Regional integration is the only way for countries such as
those in Southeast Asia to make their way in the world," it added.
</P>
<P>
It also said regional integration is being promoted through the
preservation of regional peace and security, increased mutual
trust and confidence and regular consultations on regional and
global security issues.
</P>
<P>
Regional economic integration is being pursued in several
forms, including the ASEAN Free Trade Area (AFTA), the ASEAN
Investment Area and the negotiations on trade in services,
tourism, transport and communication, energy, agriculture and
other fields.
</P>
<P>
Regional economic integration means bringing down barriers to
trade in goods and services, dismantling obstacles to investments,
and building transportation, communications and energy linkages
within ASEAN.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN has decided to further accelerate the implementation of
AFTA, with the six original signatories -- Brunei, Indonesia,
Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore and Thailand -- ready to
advance the completion of AFTA by one year from the year 2003 to
2002. The newer signatories will maximize the number of their
tariff lines subject to tariffs of 0-5 percent, by 2003 for
Vietnam and 2005 for Laos and Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
Trends in economic globalization need to be matched by reforms
in the global financial system, the secretary-general's report
said.
</P>
<P>
It said the Asian financial crisis is a result of rapid
financial liberalization without the commensurate strengthening of
regulation and supervision of the sector and the crisis has
exposed the weaknesses in the financial system both at the
national and corporate levels.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN should continue to address the dysfunctions resulting
from the interaction of a highly sophisticated global financial
system with the less developed domestic financial systems of
developing economies, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Reforms in the financial system are needed to improve corporate
governance toward greater efficiency, transparency and
accountability, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It also said consultations with China, Japan and South Korea
were held to exchange views on monitoring short-term capital flows
and international financial reform. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0160 </DOCNO>
