<HEADLINE> Manila Optimistic About Peso's Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government on
Thursday voiced its confidence on the peso's stability despite the
currency's depreciation caused by the weakening of the Japanese
yen.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in a radio interview Thursday morning, Finance
Secretary Edgardo Espiritu said other Asian currencies also
depreciated as a result of the mild fall of the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
"The Philippine Central Bank won't intervene if this is the
case. The peso did not depreciate because of speculation,"
Espiritu noted.
</P>
<P>
"Our dollar reserves are good. The inflow of our capital
investments, as well as the remittances of overseas Filipino
workers have not changed," he added.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the depreciation has been relatively mild,
with the exchange rate going down by 5 to 8 centavos against the
U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
"So long as the foreign exchange rate does not fall by 50
centavos or one peso, there's nothing to worry about. Our dollar
reserves are fine," he said.
</P>
<P>
Espiritu also expressed confidence that the government can keep
interest rates down because of its sound financial position.
</P>
<P>
"Our financial position is good. Our cash balance can reach 90
billion pesos ( 2.25 billion dollars) at any given time," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
