<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran will put into operation 67 telecommunications
projects in the western Hamadan province next week, the country's
Islamic Republic News Agency has reported.
</P>
<P>
Managing Director of Hamadan Telecommunications Company
Mohammad Reza Zohrevand said on Wednesday that the costs of the
projects were estimated at 75 billion Iranian rials (about 25
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The projects include traffic telecommunications centers,
digital phone centers, development of cellular phones, inter-city
switch code centers and 40 telecommunications offices, the news
agency quoted Zohrevand as saying.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- In the first half of 1999, Israel Air Industries
company (IAI) secured a 75 percent rise of its gross product to
1.4 billion dollars in commodities trade and services from the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
An IAI report published by Israel's financial daily Globes on
Wednesday said the company's aircraft division and electronics
division achieved a marked increase in production during the first
six months this year.
</P>
<P>
The report said IAI will have an estimated 2 billion dollars
worth of sales this year.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt collected 44 billion Egyptian pounds (12.94
billion dollars) of tax revenues in 1998, the Arabic-language Al
Hayat newspaper reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The government is looking forward to an increase in tax
revenues to some 60 billion pounds (17.65 billion dollars) in
1999, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 tax revenues accounted for 15.8 percent of the gross
domestic product.
</P>
<P>
RAMALLA -- The World Bank has agreed to extend a loan of 54
million dollars to the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) for
three development projects in the West Bank and the Gaza Strip.
</P>
<P>
According to a bank statement carried by Al Hayat newspaper on
Thursday, the loan should be repaid at an annual interest rate of
0.75 percent in 40 years with a 10-year grace period.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank has offered PNA 267.5 million dollars in loans
for 16 development projects in the West Bank and the Gaza Strip.
</P>
