<HEADLINE> UN Envoy Describes Tashkent Talks as "Constructive" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Secretary General's
special envoy on Afghanistan, Lakhdar Brahimi, described the
latest meeting between the warring Afghan factions in Tashkent as
"constructive."
</P>
<P>
Talking to official Afghan news agency Bakhtar in Kabul
Wednesday night upon his arrival from Uzbekistan, Brahimi lauded
the participation by the Taliban militia in the two-day peace
talks this week sponsored by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
According to a report from Kabul Thursday, Brahimi is to hold
talks with Taliban leaders on his peace mission.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban and the opposition Northern Alliance sit with
representatives from Six plus Two (Afghanistan's six immediate
neighbors plus Russia and the United States) countries and
discussed ways to put an end to the long-standing crisis in
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
However, the Taliban and the Northern Alliance failed to reach
agreement on ending their conflict at the two-day peace talks
winding up Tuesday, saying more diplomacy was needed to stop the
fighting. 
</P>
