<HEADLINE> Canadian Team to Inquire Soldier Health Problem in Croatia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- A Canadian team of experts will be
sent to Croatia Thursday to investigate the alleged soldier health
problem caused by contamination, local television reports said.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian Broadcasting Corporation (CBC) said a board of
inquiry would be set up to look into the matter involving almost 1,
000 Canadian soldiers serving in Croatia in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers were alleged to have exposed to hazardous
substances such as PCBs and bauxite used to build bankers and fill
sandbags.
</P>
<P>
A memo written by a Canadian Forces doctor recognized that a
soldier had been "exposed to bauxite and PCBs for six months"
before he suffered severe health problems since returning to
Canada.
</P>
<P>
But when the soldier, former warrant officer Matt Stopford,
later checked his own file, there was no memo, the CBC reported.
</P>
<P>
Further investigation showed the memo had been removed from
almost 1,000 soldiers' files on orders of an unidentified senior
officer and burned, the CBC report said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, CTV news reported that soil and water samples taken
from bunkers also disappeared.
</P>
<P>
Walter Natynczyk of the Canadian Defense Department told the
CTV that "the board of inquiry will establish: Was the soil
contaminated, who served at the sites and will link, if there is
indeed a link, the liability of the Canadian forces."
</P>
<P>
Stopford, who has decaying joints and only 20 percent vision in
his right eye, received a letter from Veterans Affairs on Tuesday
acknowledging his illness was due to his service in Croatia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
