<HEADLINE> Israeli Police Prevent Rightist Group from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 22 (Reuters) -- Israeli police Thursday
prevented members of a right-wing Jewish group from visiting the
Temple Mount in Jerusalem, citing "sensitive situation" following
confrontation between rightist Jews and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Ra'anan Tal, police commander in charge of the Mount area,
told reporters that he could not permit the Jewish group Temple
Mount Faithful to enter the Al-Aqsa Mosque complex atop the
mountain, a move could spark conflict between Israeli and
Palestinian worshipers.
</P>
<P>
This decision was made after scuffle broke out between
Palestinians and members of the outlawed Jewish group Kach, who
threw pamphlets onto the site shortly after the beginning of the
Jewish holiday Tisha Be'av Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
Jews pray and fast to observe Tisha Be'av, which commemorates
the destruction of the First Temple by the Babylonians in 586 BC
and the Second Temple by the Romans in 70 AD.
</P>
<P>
Israel's High Court ruled Tuesday that small groups of the
Temple Mount Faithful be allowed in principle to visit the
mountain on condition that they do not pray there on the Jewish
holiday.
</P>
<P>
As they usually do, Muslim authorities at the mosque complex
announced the closing of the Temple Mount to visitors Thursday,
citing "the sensitivity of the situation" following Wednesday's
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
The Temple Mount Faithful has attempted to rebuild the Jewish
temple at the site of the Al-Aqsa Mosque compound, where they
said the ancient Jewish temples stood.
</P>
<P>
In October 1990, this rightist group tried to lay a
cornerstone for the Third Temple on the mountain, triggering
standoff between thousands of Israeli and Palestinian worshipers.
</P>
<P>
Twenty people were killed and more than 150 others injured in
the ensuing conflict, the bloodiest since Israel seized the Arab
East Jerusalem in 1967. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
