<HEADLINE> Tanzania Plans to Quit COMESA: Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Tanzania has announced that
it plans to pull out of the 20-member Common Market for Eastern
and Southern Africa (COMESA).
</P>
<P>
"We have done some research and found out that it is best for
us to quit COMESA", said Iddi Simba, Minister of Industries and
Commerce, according to The Guardian newspaper Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Consultations on procedures for our pull-out are proceeding,"
Simba said in the central city Dodoma Wednesday while presenting
his ministry's 1999/2000 budget estimates before the National
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
He was quoted by the largest private paper as saying that the
government' s decision to pull out of COMESA was prompted by the
proposal to reduce customs tariffs for member countries by 90
percent.
</P>
<P>
Before the government's decision to withdraw from COMESA,
Tanzania reduced by 80 percent the tariffs through an act in 1998,
he said.
</P>
<P>
"Currently, the tariff rate for COMESA member states is on
average seven percent. However, it is expected to fall to four
percent once the 90 percent reduction is implemented," Simba said.
</P>
<P>
Apart from announcing the decision to withdraw from COMESA,
Simba reiterated the government's commitment to intensify economic
cooperation with Kenya and Uganda through the East African
Co-operation (EAC).
</P>
<P>
Tanzania, Kenya and Uganda, members of the EAC, are preparing
to sign a treaty this year to upgrade their cooperation level by
establishing the East African Community, which aims to create a
common market between the three countries, to be followed by a
monetary union and ultimately a political federation.
</P>
<P>
COMESA, which was set up in 1994, includes Ethiopia, Angola,
Burundi, Zimbabwe, the Comoros, Kenya, Lesotho, Rwanda, Malawi,
Mauritius, Mozambique, Swaziland, Sudan, Tanzania, Uganda,
Zambia, Congo (K), Eritrea, Madagascar and Namibia.
</P>
<P>
Sources told Xinhua Thursday that Tanzania, a member of both
COMESA and Southern Africa Development Community (SADC), has long
considered quitting one of the two because of financial
difficulties in paying membership fees.
</P>
<P>
The minister also said that Tanzania, which is the industry
coordinator of the SADC, would continue to push for zero customs
duty tariffs for the 14-member SADC states, through its ambassador
in Geneva, Ali Mchumo, who is the chairman of the World Trade
Organization's General Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
