<HEADLINE> Toronto Listed Top Canadian Growth City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Canada's largest metropolis Toronto
is estimated to lead other cities of the country in 1999, with a
GDP growth of at least four percent, according to the latest
forecast by the Conference Board of Canada.
</P>
<P>
The Ottawa-based agency says that for the third consecutive
year, Toronto keeps the No.1 growth rate as every sector of its
economy is firing.
</P>
<P>
Low taxes are attracting investment and people in demand of
more housing to bring more jobs and greater spending to the city,
the agency says in its study of the economies of nine major
Canadian cities.
</P>
<P>
Southern Ontario's strong links with the booming U.S. economy
is also listed as a key factor for Toronto's economic growth,
especially in the automotive and manufacturing sectors.
</P>
<P>
The rapidly growing high-tech sector is giving rise to a 3.9
percent growth in Ottawa and neighboring Hull, securing the No.2
position for both cities, as illustrated by the study.
</P>
<P>
The downsizing in the federal public service has also
contributed to the economic growth in Ottawa, the study says.
</P>
<P>
The Alberta capital Edmonton ranks third in the study with a
predicted 3.2 percent growth to be fueled in 1999 by strong gains
in the construction sector, along with growing chemical and
industrial investments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
