<HEADLINE> Philippines, Singapore Sign Accord on IT Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines and Singapore have
signed an agreement to develop their respective information
technology (IT) sectors, Philippine News Agency (PNA) reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The document was signed Wednesday by Philippine Science
Undersecretary Rogelio Panlasigui and Michael Yap of the National
Computer Board (NCB) of Singapore, PNA said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was part of the 1998 Philippine-Singapore Action
Plan, a partnership that Panlasigui said "would allow the two
countries to develop and sustain a competitive edge in the
information technology sector."
</P>
<P>
Panlasigui said, "The two countries could jointly develop
products for the world market by combining, for example,
multimedia creative talent in the Philippines with project
management and marketing expertise in Singapore."
</P>
<P>
Panlasigui also hoped that Singapore could also "help in the
Philippines' efforts to establish an Internet backbone by sharing
its experience in setting up SingaporeONE (One Network for
Everyone).
</P>
<P>
SingaporeONE is the world's first nationwide broadband network
that provides easy Internet access to every home, school and
office in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The two countries could also explore the possibility of
establishing a high-speed telecommunications link to ease the flow
of communications, information and transactions between the two
nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
