<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Troops to Phase out S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian troops in the West Africa
Peace Keeping Force or ECOMOG in Sierra Leone will kick off its
gradual withdrawal from August 26, reported a Nigerian news paper
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian Federal Executive Council (FEC) made the decision
Wednesday at one of its meetings, according to the Post Express,
a leading Nigerian daily.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian Information Minister Dapo Sarumi said after the
meeting that the withdrawal will be in phases.
</P>
<P>
Nigerian government is reportedly to have set aside funds in
its supplementary budget for the troops back home. The money will
be used in areas including repairing Nigerian Air force's
Hercules C-130 transporters, which are to be used to fly back the
solders.
</P>
<P>
The gradual phasing out of Nigerian troops from Sierra Leone is
in line with an election promise of President Olusegun Obasanjo,
who played an important role in helping signing a peace accord
between Sierra Leonean government and the rebels on July 7.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria has a share of 11,000 solders in the ECOMOG's 15,000
strong military presence in the war-torn west African country.
</P>
<P>
It is widely believed that Nigeria's withdrawal is primarily
based on economic considerations. Nigeria has in the past urged
international community including the United Nations to pay for
its staying in the country but only got partial assistance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
