<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australians Rally Against U.S. Restrictions on Lamb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- More than 700 farmers and
protesters rallied in central Sydney Thursday to protest against
U.S. trade restrictions on Australian lamb.
</P>
<P>
Chefs wearing U.S. President Bill Clinton rubber masks and
others donning Uncle Sam hats served up cuts of lamb to
protesters, billing it as the "tasty meats the White House won't
serve."
</P>
<P>
The rally marks the start of a National Meat and Livestock
Australia Association campaign to encourage Australians to eat
more lamb.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman for the campaign James Kilmartin described the
protest as a way of drawing attention to what he called a serious
problem -- the "unfair" trade restrictions.
</P>
<P>
He said that although the United States is a big overseas
market, local consumers could help offset the blow dealt by the
new tariffs.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Thursday, Australian Trade Minister Mark Vaile
announced an assistance package of up to 14 million Australian
dollars (9.24 million U.S. dollars) to help Australia's lamb
industry following the U.S. import restrictions.
</P>
<P>
Vaile also criticized the U.S. decision on Australian lamb,
saying Australia would not follow "the unjust, myopic and sadly
protectionist move" of the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration decided on July 7 to impose a quota
of 31,851 metric tons on lamb imports from Australia, New Zealand
and some other countries.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a tariff of 9 percent for sales within the quota was
claimed and a punishing rate for sales outside that quota was up
to 40 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
