<HEADLINE> Nigerian Government Assures Safety in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 22 (Xinhua) -- A Nigerian government delegation
Wednesday commiserated with the Hausa and Yoruba communities in
Sagamu where communal clash claimed about 20 lives at the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
The Guardian, a major Nigerian newspaper, reported Thursday
that the delegation led by Internal Affairs Minister Sunday
Afolabi, appealed for calm and assured that adequate measures
have been put in place to ensure safety of life and property.
</P>
<P>
Afolabi said the president "was worried and as a result, he
said we should come and commiserate with you (Kabiyesi), the
people of Sagamu and the Hausa community."
</P>
<P>
President Olusegun Obasanjo also thanked the state government
for taking charge of the situation as this "helped to reduce the
scale of the incident. " He assured that the federal and state
governments were working together to ensure that lives and
property were preserved.  He urged paramount rulers to continue
to maintain peace in their areas while law enforcement agents
were urged not to take sides.  
</P>
</TEXT>
