<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Share Prices Plummet in Tokyo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices nosedived in Tokyo
Thursday on profit-taking stirred by the U.S. dollar's fall
against the yen, with the key Nikkei index closing below 18,000
for the first time in nearly two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange slid 527.18 points, or 2.89
percent, from Wednesday's close to end at 17,730.34, marking the
second-largest single-day decline of this year.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, lost 41.09 points or 2.74 percent to 1,459.
02.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section decreased to 542.34 million
shares from 655.84 million shares Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Japan's major trading house Itochu Corp. was the day's volume
leader.
</P>
<P>
Share prices were down in all business sectors, export-oriented
high-tech blue chips were particularly lower, hit by the weak
dollar.traders said.
</P>
<P>
The dollar was traded at 118.53-56 yen at 3 p.m. in Tokyo, down
from 118.98-119.01 late Wednesday, despite dollar-supportive
market intervention by the Bank of Japan (BOJ) on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Foreign investors, the major driving force in the Tokyo stock
market, turned to be net sellers of Japanese stocks, urging
domestic investors to sell stocks as well, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers outnumbered
gainers 1,121 to 135, with 71 issues ending unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
