<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN's New Members Urged to Foster Private Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Newer members of the Association
of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) should strengthen their private
sectors, Rodolfo Severino, secretary-general of the regional
grouping, said here on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a conference of the ASEAN Business Forum, Severino
said the private sector has to play the "primary role" in a "world
of globalization and regionalization."
</P>
<P>
All countries in ASEAN, especially newer ones like Cambodia,
Laos, Myanmar and Vietnam, should strengthen their private
sectors, he said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups all the 10 countries in Southeast Asia --
Singapore, Vietnam, Cambodia, Laos, Brunei, Indonesia, the
Philippines, Malaysia, Myanmar and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Building up private business in the newer members, he said, is
necessary for the regional business networking that is required by
the growing integration of the regional economy.
</P>
<P>
"If the huge market that is ASEAN Ten is to be exploited to
full advantage," he stressed, "the horizons of ASEAN business must
expand to embrace the newer ASEAN members as well as the old."
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN secretary-general was speaking on the eve of the 32nd
ASEAN Ministerial Meeting (AMM), which is scheduled for Friday and
Saturday and will be attended by all the 10 ASEAN members.
</P>
<P>
The AMM will be followed by the ASEAN Regional Forum and Post
Ministerial Conference, at which ASEAN foreign ministers will hold
talks with their counterparts from Russia, the European Union, the
United States, China and Japan, among others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
