<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Govt Urged to Assist Small Scale Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Zambian government has been urged
to assist small scale farmers because they produce about 70
percent of the country's food security requirements.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Daily Mail newspaper Thursday quoted Copperbelt
Minister Matthew Mulanda as saying in a speech at a land workshop
held in Kitwe, Copperbelt Province, that the government assured
Britain's OXFAM and other developmental organizations that it
established a land registry in Ndola, north Zambia, with a view to
addressing problems being faced by the vulnerable farming
community.
</P>
<P>
He implored stake-holders to seriously consider how they could
create an enabling environment for greater agricultural growth.
</P>
<P>
OXFAM program manager Mahongo Shibemba said although small
scale farmers produce more food for the nation, the majority
illegally settle on land owned by forestry and absentee landlords.
</P>
<P>
Shibemba said peasant farmers fear to increase production due
to the ever imminent possibility of eviction.
</P>
<P>
She said most of the small scale producers were not squatters
by choice but were relegated to the position by a land acquisition
procedure that is long and expensive.
</P>
<P>
Shibemba complained on behalf of the farming community that it
takes too long for a farmer to get a title to his plot because of
red tape.
</P>
<P>
She attributed the sad development to lack of information on
where to go and how to own land legally.
</P>
<P>
Shibemba appealed to Zambian government to honor their promise
of protecting the poor so that they are able to produce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
