<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 08:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian Committee Eyes Tougher Penalty for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 22 (Xinhua) -- A special Jordanian committee has
decided to cancel law provisions which reduce or even pardon
alleged honor killings which claimed lives of dozens of young
women in the kingdom every year.
</P>
<P>
The amendment to the Penal of Code by the special committee
under the Ministry of Justice has yet to be approved by the lower
and upper houses of the parliament and then to be followed by a
Royal decree, Minister of Justice Hamzeh Haddad was quoted as
saying by the semiofficial Jordan Times Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The committee decided to cancel the entire article 340 of the
Penal Code which dealt with honor killings, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The decision by the committee was apparently a result of
pressure from women`s rights groups which had complained for years
against some clauses in the Penal Code concerning the alleged
honor crimes, which claimed lives of an average of 25 women
annually in the 1990s in the desert kingdom.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian King Abdullah Bin Hussein also intervened after he
took the throne early this year and ordered the government to
amend any laws that discriminate against the rights of women and
inflict injustice on women. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Space Shuttle Columbia Launch Aborted Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Bad weather prevented U.S.
space shuttle Columbia from blasting off early Thursday morning in
Cape Canaveral, Florida State, with Eileen Collins, the first
woman to lead a U.S. space flight.
</P>
<P>
After aborting the first scheduled launch with six seconds
remaining just after midnight Tuesday because of a faulty sensor,
launch controllers were forced to scrub it again early Thursday
when a lightning storm moved into the area.
</P>
<P>
Lightning flashed offshore and thunder rumbled as the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) held the countdown at
the five-minute mark in hopes that the storms would pass by
quickly.
</P>
<P>
The launch director even added 10 minutes to the launch window,
but it didn't help. He waited until the last possible moment
before radioing the bad news to Collins and her crew: they would
not be lifting off Thursday with the world's most powerful X-ray
telescope.
</P>
<P>
NASA said it would try again early Friday.
</P>
<P>
The first launch attempt, on Tuesday, ended six seconds before
liftoff when a dangerous hydrogen buildup was detected in the
engine compartment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
