<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Members Meet to Finally Approve Leadership Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The ruling General Council of the
World Trade Organization (WTO) began the formal meeting here
Thursday to formally approve a power-sharing plan to appoint Mike
Moore of New Zealand and Supachai Panithpakdi of Thailand as the
WTO's next two consecutive leaders.
</P>
<P>
In the revised version of the draft plan for approval on
Thursday, the key word "by consensus" has been deleted because
certain WTO members do not fully agree to the wording, according
to trade sources close to the closed-door meeting.
</P>
<P>
During an informal meeting Tuesday at the WTO headquarters,
trade envoys of the WTO's 134 members discussed the draft "3+3"
plan brokered by Bangladesh and Australia.
</P>
<P>
If the plan is approved, Mike Moore of New Zealand will be
appointed as Director-General for three years from September 1,
1999 to August 31, 2002. Supachai Panitchpakdi of Thailand would
succeed Moore from September 1, 2002 for three years to August 31,
2005.
</P>
<P>
Neither of the candidates should be eligible for re-appointment
as Director-General nor should his period of office be extended,
according to the proposal. It stressed that the special
arrangement for the two candidates should not be the precedent for
future appointments of the WTO chief.
</P>
<P>
Normally, the term of office of the WTO chief is four years
like former WTO Director-General Renato Ruggiero has served.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 09:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Says Syria Keeps Sending Positive Signals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Foreign Minister David
Levy said Thursday that Israel had received further signals from
Syrian President Hafez al-Assad that Damascus is interested in
resuming peace talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Levy told Israel's Army Radio that he was briefed by visiting
Spanish Prime Minister Jose Maria Aznar that Assad does not want
to waste an opportunity to make peace with Israel's new Prime
Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
Aznar, who is in Israel at the last stop of his five-day
Middle East tour, met Assad Monday. He will hold talks later
Thursday with Barak, who returned from a six-day visit to
Washington Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Mr Assad is apparently convinced of Israel's intentions for
peace and it seems he is determined not to waste the
opportunity," Levy told the radio.
</P>
<P>
Ousting hard-line Benjamin Netanyahu in the prime ministerial
election in May, Barak has pledged to push forward the peace
process with Syria as well as the Palestinians, which was largely
frozen in the last three years.
</P>
<P>
He promised to resume the peace talks with Damascus under the
framework of U.N. Resolutions 242 and 338, which call for Israel
to relinquish Arab land it occupied in the 1967 Middle East war,
including the strategic plateau of Golan Heights of Syria.
</P>
<P>
Since his election victory, Barak has traded compliments and
trust-building signals with Assad, the former arch-foe in the
battlefield.
</P>
<P>
There have been reports that Damascus has asked radical
Palestinian groups based in Syria to stop armed struggle against
Israel. Barak welcomed the reports.
</P>
<P>
Israel's army chief admitted Wednesday that Syria is also
taking action to restrain Hezbollah guerrillas, who are fighting
to oust Israel from its occupation zone in southern Lebanon, from
firing Katyusha rockets into northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
After meeting Barak in Washington this week, U.S. President
Bill Clinton called on Assad to seize the current "golden
opportunity" to reach peace with Israel. U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright is expected to shuttle in the region next
month, likely to include a visit to Damascus.
</P>
<P>
Barak's chief of staff Danny Yatom said the Israeli-Syrian
talks might be resumed in a matter of weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
