<HEADLINE> Kenya's National Census Underway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The preliminary results of Kenya's
1999 national population and housing census will be released
within three months as the census falls on August 24 and 25,
Kenyan Vice-President George Saitoti has said.
</P>
<P>
This would be possible because the event's national steering
committee had acquired sophisticated scanners which would expedite
the processing of data, he said when addressing the members of
the steering committee Wednesday in the capital Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
Everything was on schedule for the big count, Saitoti said,
adding the recruitment of census personnel had also taken place
and currently, supervisors and enumerators were undergoing
training, the Daily Nation newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the recruitment had emphasized on taking
personnel from the same localities they would count local people.
</P>
<P>
The steering committee was also putting in place security
measures to ensure criminals do not have a field-day during the
census, he added.
</P>
<P>
The count is expected to cost about two billion shilling (some
30 million U.S. dollars) provided by the government budget and
several donors.
</P>
<P>
Saitoti urged the public to be adequately informed about the
need of participation and given correct information during the
exercise, called on the secretariat to conduct advocacy seminars
in various districts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
