<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Trade Deficit Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon witnessed a downward trade
deficit in the first half of 1999 as exports rose and imports
declined, the Daily Star newspaper reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The trade deficit dropped by 15.2 percent to 2.68 billion U.S.
dollars in the first half of this year from 3.16 billion dollars
in the same period last year, the English-language newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The exports rose by 12 percent to 356 million dollars in the
first six months this year, compared to 319 million dollars during
the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the imports fell by 13 percent to 3.04 billion
dollars in the first half of 1999, compared to 3.5 billion
dollars in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Among the exports, jewelry and precious stones, worth a total
of 54 million dollars, took the lion's share of exports with 15
percent, followed by electrical and mechanical appliances with
13.28 percent, valued at 47 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The export of metal products accounted for 38 million dollars,
or 10.79 percent of the total exports and was ranked the third.
Chemical products, worth 33 million dollars, or 9.18 percent, came
in fourth.
</P>
<P>
Electrical and mechanical appliances with a value of 473
million dollars, representing 15.6 percent of total imports,
constituted the country's major category of imports, followed by
cars and vehicles, worth 301 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Chemical products valued at 290 million dollars came third at
9.56 percent, followed by mineral products, worth 243 million
dollars and an 8 percent share. 
</P>
</TEXT>
