<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Lobby in Brunei For 2006 Asian Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia is looking to exploit
the arena of the upcoming Southeast Asian (SEA) Games by trying to
lobby the participating countries with regard to its plan to bid
for the 2006 Asian Games, The Indonesian Observer reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
General Secretary of the Indonesian Sports Council (KONI)
Rudolf Warrow said that Indonesia would plan to invite the top
officials of the participating teams to a cocktail party on August
6, or one day before the opening ceremony.
</P>
<P>
"They may have known over our plan of the 2006 Asian Games but
we'll be pressing ahead to declare officially our intention to bid,
" Rudolf said.
</P>
<P>
He said that Indonesia would use the occasion to push ahead
with the aspirations to form a pencak silat federation in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Rudolf said between 30 and 40 invitees were expected to turn up
in a night of ceremony which would be accompanied by the display
of the items highlighting the hype of the 2006 Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
Apart from Indonesia, Malaysia has also announced its intention
along with the United Arab Emirates, India, Kuwait and Hong Kong
of China.
</P>
<P>
The Asian Olympics Committee will decide on the winner in
November 2000. The bidders are expected to submit the
administration requirements at the general assembly in Kuwait in
November this year.
</P>
<P>
Rudolf said that Indonesia did not have a plan to build other
new venues except for the establishment of an athletes' compound
which should accommodate as many as 10,000.
</P>
<P>
On Indonesia's chance in the bidding given the ongoing economic
condition, Rudolf was left saying: "as a nation we must be
optimistic that the future will be getting better."
</P>
<P>
He said the government's pledge in supporting the plan had
thrown up moral support behind the campaign.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia hosted its first and only Asian Games in 1962.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
