<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Deal with Israel over Arrested Jews </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Iran has denied reports that it was
seeking a deal with Israel over the release of the 13 Iranian Jews
arrested on charge of spying for Israel, Iran's Tehran Times daily
reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"It is like a bad joke and carries no truth," Iranian Foreign
Ministry spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi said in an interview with the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Asefi was responding to a report carried by the Israeli Yedioth
Ahronoth daily on Wednesday that Israel has rejected a proposal
made by Iran for a deal over the 13 arrested Iranian Jews.
</P>
<P>
The daily said that Israel rejects any link between the 13
Iranian Jews, of whom Israel is trying to seek the release, and
any other disputes between the two countries, including Iran's
claim that Israel owes it 1 billion U.S. dollars from the days
before the 1979 Islamic revolution.
</P>
<P>
"In general, from our point of view, the Zionist (Israeli)
regime lacks legitimacy," Asefi said. "We do not officially
recognize it, therefore, such rumors are published for propaganda
purposes."
</P>
<P>
The Iranian spokesman said the Israeli anti-Iran propaganda
would not have any impact on the international public opinion on
Iran.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Tehran Times said an Iranian informed source has
confirmed Iran's claim on Israel's debts, but saying that "the
principles and sanctities of the Islamic revolution are more
important than dollars."
</P>
<P>
Israel and western countries have urged Iran to release the 13
Iranian Jews as both Israel and the United States have denied any
links between their intelligence services and the arrested Jews.
</P>
<P>
Iran has turned down the calls for the release of the Jews, but
promised to give them a fair trial according to Iranian laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
