<HEADLINE> Dhaka Puts Off Myanmar Minister's Visit to Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has asked Myanmar
Commerce Minister Kyaw Than postpone his scheduled August 3-7
visit to Dhaka till December, The Daily Star newspaper reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Quoting competent sources, a front-paged report in the
newspaper said Dhaka's decision was communicated to Yangon on
Wednesday, which was seen as a diplomatic response to Myanmar's
non-committal stance on the issue of refugee repatriation.
</P>
<P>
The date of the Myanmar commerce minister's visit was confirmed
by Foreign Minister U Win Aung when he was on a trip here earlier
this week.
</P>
<P>
Yangon's failure to give a concrete assurance for the return of
some 21,000 stranded Rohingya refugees during the Myanmar foreign
minister's visit may have prompted Dhaka to ask for the
postponement, the report said.
</P>
<P>
But officials from the Commerce Ministry denied that the
postponement was linked with the refugee issue, saying that
Bangladeshi Commerce Minister Tonal Ahmed would be unavailable in
Dhaka during the period.
</P>
<P>
They said Ahmed would have to leave for Male, the Maldives
early next month to attend a SAARC (South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation) commerce ministers' meeting, and would visit
some other countries in the capacity as the spokesperson of the
Least Developed Countries for WTO-related issues.
</P>
<P>
The report said it was a big disappointment for Bangladesh that
the Myanmar foreign minister did not give any concrete assurance
regarding that fate of the large number of Rohingya refugees who
have been staying in two UNHCR camps in Cox's Bazar, southeastern
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Dhaka was expecting that the stalled repatriation process would
resume after the visit of the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar has taken back some 230,000 refugees out of more than
250,000 since the Rohingya refugees crossed the Bangladeshi border
in 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
