<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Letters Express Support for Japanese Veteran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- More than 5,700 letters and wall
scrolls from China and other countries have been sent here since
early December in 1998 expressing support for Shiro Azuma, the
Japanese veteran who published his wartime diary recording the
atrocities committed by Japanese soldiers in China during World
War II.
</P>
<P>
The letters and scrolls also express strong protests against
the Tokyo Higher Court's ruling against Shiro Azuma.
</P>
<P>
These letters and scrolls have come from all over China, the
United States, Denmark, the Republic of Korea (ROK), and Thailand
and Malaysia, and were signed by 55,110 people.
</P>
<P>
Most of them extend a firm support to Shiro Azuma, and urge the
Tokyo Higher Court to respect history and judge justly.
</P>
<P>
The Jiangdongmen Memorial Hall here in east China's Jiangsu
Province, which was built to commemorate the victims of the
Nanjing Massacre that claimed the lives of 300,000 unarmed Chinese
soldiers and civilians in 1937, is now processing these letters
and scrolls.
</P>
<P>
A Japanese association supporting Shiro Azuma has decided to
take some of these letters to Japan as evidence to be presented to
the Japanese Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
Shiro Azuma, recruited into the Japanese army and sent to China
in 1937, was engaged in intruding battles to occupy major Chinese
cities including Tianjin, Shanghai, Nanjing, Xuzhou, and Wuhan,
and recorded all this in his diary.
</P>
<P>
He published part of the diary in Japan in 1987, but was later
sued by a former soldier who was described in the diary as a war
criminal.
</P>
<P>
The Tokyo Higher Court ruled in this man's favor and instructed
that his name should not be made known or any action taken against
him.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
