<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Sector Enjoys Better Performance in Tianjin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Intensified reform and industrial
restructuring has enabled the state sector in northern China's
Tianjin Municipality to reverse a declining trend and begin to
enjoy an upturn.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics from the city show that state industrial
output increased by 6.4 percent during the first six months this
year, with the output of the large- and medium-sized enterprises
rising 6.62 percent on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
Technological renovation of the state sector is the major
reason behind the upturn. The municipal government has accelerated
these renovations in recent years, initiating high-tech projects
in the sector and introducing overseas capital into them to
upgrade their technological level.
</P>
<P>
A total of 352 million US dollars in overseas investment has
come into 21 technological renovations projects in the state
enterprises in Tianjin during the first five months this year.
</P>
<P>
Competitive products with good market prospects were developed
as a result of the technological renovations, which have become a
new growth point for the state sector. Statistics showed that
Tianjin achieved 9.8 billion yuan (1.18 billion US dollars) in
output value from 850 items of newly developed products during the
first half this year.
</P>
<P>
Large state enterprise groups also received support from the
municipal government to increase economic efficiency, and the ten
largest enterprises in electronics, light industry, and machinery
in Tianjin realized nearly 50 percent of their industrial added
value during the January-May period.
</P>
<P>
To pull the state sector out of difficulties, Tianjin has
turned 114 large- and medium-sized state enterprises into joint-
stock companies, merging 17 inefficient enterprises during the
first six months this year. Of the 38 deficit-ridden state
enterprises, the municipal government has helped seven erase their
deficits and achieve profits, with 23 reducing deficits by wide
margins. 
</P>
</TEXT>
