<HEADLINE> Vietnam's Biggest Economic Hub to Boost Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The Ho Chi Minh City People's
Committee has decided to spend 5,335 billion Vietnamese dong (384
million U.S. dollars) to develop socio-economic infrastructure to
boost the local production, Vietnam's English daily Vietnam News
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Money will be used to upgrade major inner city roads,
bridges, water supply systems, residential housing, hospitals,
schools, and to buy new equipment in an effort to stimulate demand
for consumption.
</P>
<P>
Ho Chi Minh City is Vietnam's biggest economic hub. In the
first six months of the year, However, the city's economy grew
slowly with the gross domestic product increasing by only 5.6
percent.
</P>
<P>
A report of the People's Committee of the city said that
although significant improvement was recorded in the second
quarter of the year, economic obstacles remained numerous, with
little hope of a return to the previous high growth rates.
</P>
<P>
A number of outstanding social problems also hinder economic
growth, such as unemployment, a population explosion caused by
immigration, a shortage of hospitals, homelessness, begging,
rampant breaches of the law, corruption and other social evils.
</P>
<P>
In the second half of this year, about 1,000 billion Vietnamese
dong (about 72 million U.S. dollars) will be invested in major
projects already approved by the Vietnamese government.
</P>
<P>
The city government will also provide more incentives to
encourage all economic sectors to invest in developing
infrastructure, purchasing advanced machinery and technology as
well as expanding markets and boosting the local production.
</P>
</TEXT>
