<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Get 33 Mln Dollars from WB for Fisheries Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank (WB) on Wednesday
announced the approval of a 28 million U.S. dollar credit and a 5
million dollar global environment facility grant for Bangladesh's
fisheries project, according to a WB press release reaching here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The credit, which will be provided by the International
Development Association, will be used for the implementation of
Bangladesh's 4th fisheries project to increase
environmentally-friendly and sustainable fish and shrimp
production.
</P>
<P>
"The objective of the project is to support
environmentally-friendly and sustainable fish and shrimp
production for domestic consumption and exports, and to help fight
poverty in Bangladesh by improving the livelihood of people who
depend on fishing," Benson Ateng, project task leader for WB's
South Asia Rural Development Unit, said.
</P>
<P>
"At full operation, the project will account for about 22,000
tons in incremental fish production and an additional 2,500 tons
of shrimp each year. The project will also provide about 440,000
additional jobs in the fishing industry, especially for the poor
and women," he added.
</P>
<P>
Fisheries is a vital industry in Bangladesh, and it accounts
for about 10 percent of agricultural GDP (gross domestic product),
three percent of GDP, eight percent of the total export earnings,
and a major source of the country's protein intake. The sector now
employs nearly two million full-time fishermen and 12 million
people working part-time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
