<HEADLINE> Former U.S. Presidents Join Appeal To Hollywood On Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Former U.S. presidents Gerald
Ford and Jimmy Carter Wednesday joined a group of prominent
Americans in an appeal to the entertainment industry to
voluntarily reduce violence and sex for the protection of children.
</P>
<P>
"We call upon industry leaders in all media, television, film,
music video and electronic games, to band together to develop a
new voluntary code of conduct," wrote the signatories of "An
Appeal to Hollywood."
</P>
<P>
"We appeal to those who are reaping great profits to give
something back," said the appeal, which was released at a Capitol
Hill news conference by a bipartisan group of senators.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the two former presidents, the 56 signatories
included Nobel Peace Prize winner Elie Wiesel, retired generals
Norman Schwarzkopf and Colin Powell, and entertainer Steve Allen.
</P>
<P>
"American parents today are deeply worried about their children
's exposure to an increasingly toxic popular culture, "the
signatories said.
</P>
<P>
The school shootings in Littleton, Colorado, three months ago
and elsewhere have rekindled efforts in Congress to pressure the
entertainment industry to curtail violence and explicit sexual
content. Fifteen people were killed in the Colorado campus
shooting.
</P>
<P>
Last month President Bill Clinton ordered a study on the
advertising of movies, music and video games to children and a
stricter enforcement of movie ratings.
</P>
<P>
The National Association of Theater Owners, in response to
Clinton's requests, agreed to check their photo identification
cards before youths are admitted into cinemas to see R-rated films.
</P>
</TEXT>
