<HEADLINE> Australian Govt Unveils Assistance Package for Lamb Producers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The Australian government
Thursday announced an assistance package of up to 14 million
Australian dollars (9.24 million U.S. dollars) to help Australia's
lamb industry following U.S. import restrictions.
</P>
<P>
Newly-appointed Trade Minister Mark Vaile made the announcement
at the New South Wales Farmers Association conference in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
The government will also establish a lamb industry development
program which costs up to 3 million Australian dollars (1.98
million U.S. dollars) a year, he said.
</P>
<P>
This funding comes on top of the 14-million-Australian dollar
package announced on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Vaile said Australia would not follow the unjust, myopic and
sadly protectionist move of the United States.
</P>
<P>
Vaile's announcement was made on the day the new U.S. tariffs
come into effect and the Australian lamb producers are to hold a
"barbie with Bill" protest.
</P>
<P>
The government will provide assistance to lamb producers by
paying for up to two years the equivalent of half the transaction
levy applying to all lamb sold in Australia.
</P>
<P>
"As the prime minister (John Howard) said very directly to the
president (Bill Clinton) in Washington, no trade issue in recent
memory has galvanized our farmers, an indeed ordinary Australians,
like the lamb dispute," Vaile said.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. decision is without a rational basis, unjust and
hypocritical," he added. 
</P>
