<HEADLINE> Japan Funds Six Major Sri Lankan Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Japan has pledged to grant Sri
Lanka 23,476 million Japanese yen (190 million U.S. dollars) as
soft loans for six development projects, Finance Ministry sources
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The exchange of letters for the six loans were signed here
Wednesday by officials on behalf of their respective countries.
</P>
<P>
This is the 32nd of the such packages extended on an annual
basis. The yen loans, granted by Overseas Economic Cooperation
Fund (OECF) of Japan, are extended on very concessionary terms,
the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The interest rates on the loans are in the range of 0.75 to 1.8
percent and are repayable in 30 to 40-year periods with a 10-year
grace period.
</P>
<P>
The largest loan is for the expansion of the Bandaranaike
International Airport in suburbs north of Colombo which includes
provision for a new passenger terminal, cargo terminal, taxi way,
apron and air navigational facilities.
</P>
<P>
Two loans have been provided for road improvement and another
for the Poverty Alleviation Micro Finance Project implemented by
the Rural Credit Department of the Central Bank.
</P>
<P>
Yet another loan has been allocated for a water supply project
to reduce wastage of water in the greater Colombo area.
</P>
<P>
The sixth loan is to finance the dredging of the north channel
of the Colombo port to open it for bigger vessels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
