<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Awards Chinese Anti-Smoking Campaigners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Two Chinese became this year's
winners of an anti-smoking award presented by the World Health
Organization (WHO) for their devotion to anti-smoking campaigns in
the world's largest tobacco-consuming country.
</P>
<P>
He Luli, vice-chairwoman of the National People's Congress
Standing Committee, and Zhang Yifang, vice-president of the
Chinese Association on Smoking and Health, received the WHO award
in Beijing on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
WHO has granted the honor to seven Chinese people and five
Chinese organizations since 1989, including renowned medical
expert Wu Jieping and former Health Minister Chen Minzhang, and
the China Central Television Station.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Health Zhang Wenkang acknowledged that health risks
from tobacco use "remain serious," despite Chinese government
efforts to control smoking since 1979.
</P>
<P>
"Tougher measures should be taken to increase health education
and curb the rising rate of smoking among teenagers," Zhang said
at the award ceremony.
</P>
<P>
A total of 320 million smokers in China makes it the world's
biggest consumer of tobacco products. Statistics from the Ministry
of Health show that the rate of smokers in China's population
increased 3.74 percentage points in the 1984-1996 period, and the
mortality rate from lung cancer, which is believed to be one
result of smoking, has risen 4.5 percent annually.
</P>
<P>
The Ministry and the Chinese Association on Smoking and Health,
the country's leading anti-smoking organization, have encouraged
85 cities to ban smoking in public places. The advertising of
tobacco products now is being phased out in major Chinese cities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
