<HEADLINE> Agronomy Improving Lives Of China's Ethnic Groups </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, July 22 (Xinhua) -- More developed agronomy has been
used on the Pamir Plateau where members of the Tajik ethnic group
live, in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
The majority of them live in the Tajik Autonomous County 4,000
meters above sea level, where there are only some 70 frost-free
days a year and an annual average of 69 mm of rainfall.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the county began experimenting with growing wheat
under plastic sheeting and they began getting yields of 4,500 kg.
per ha, three times the previous highest output of highland barley.
The technique was then applied to elsewhere in China last year and
grain outputs reached 5,300 tons, 1,300 tons more than for the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
This relatively poor county produced more than enough food
grain for the first time in history last year, greatly increasing
farmers' enthusiasm for more modern agronomy, says an official in
charge the county's agriculture and forestry.
</P>
<P>
The county has trained 60 technicians who show farmers how to
grow vegetables in greenhouses and how to improve the breeds of
animals. Artificial insemination and other forms of breeding have
helped local farmers improve 80 percent of their 90,000 big-tail
sheep and experiment with crossing cattle and yaks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
