<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Retains No.33 in 1999 Global Competitiveness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines has retained a rank
of No. 33 in the World Economic Forum's 1999 Global
Competitiveness Report, the newspaper Today said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report, which rates 59 countries around the world in terms
of the factors that allow economies to compete in the global
market, is made up of eight factors of competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines ranked 38th in finance, 41st in technology,
24th in management, 42nd in openness, 12th in government, 46th in
infrastructure, 28th in labor, and 49th in the strength of its
institutions.
</P>
<P>
The country's rankings for openness, government,
infrastructure, labor and strength of institutions all dropped in
the past year while it showed improvement in the finance,
technology, and management factors.
</P>
<P>
In terms of microeconomic competitiveness factors, the
Philippines improved marginally from 45th in 1998 to 44th this
year.
</P>
<P>
The report said staff training programs, marketing expertise,
customer orientation, quality of business education, and financial
market sophistication gave the Philippines some additional
competitive edge. But the country continues to be pulled back by
handicaps in its air transport infrastructure, telephone/fax
infrastructure, and the extent of "irregular payments," or
corruption. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
