<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Armed Groups Urged Not to Use Children in War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Children's Fund (UNICEF) on Wednesday called for the definite
elimination of the use of children and minors, below the age of 18,
in armed conflicts in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held at the U.N. body's Colombian
headquarters, Cecilio Adorno, UNICEF director for Latin America
and the Caribbean, requested all the Colombians to end "the horror
of the continuous use of children as a weapon to win the war."
</P>
<P>
Citing statistics from Colombia's Defense Council, Adorno said
there were 6,000 minors linked to the country's armed groups
between 1996 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
"On some of the guerrilla fronts, more than 30 percent of the
activists are children, and in some cases the proportion of
children in the paramilitary units is higher than 50 percent," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
