<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expanded Enrollment to Bolster Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- An increase in the number of
students enrolling in college this year is expected to give a shot
in the arm to sluggish domestic consumption, today's "China Daily"
reports.
</P>
<P>
The State Development Planning Commission (SDPC) and the
Ministry of Education announced in the middle of last month that
the country will enroll 331,000 college students more than
originally planned.
</P>
<P>
This means that 1.53 million of the 3.4 million students who
took part in this month's entrance examination will be admitted to
college.
</P>
<P>
"The average college student spends about 10,000 yuan (1,200 U.
S. dollars) a year on tuition fees, accommodation and living
expenses, so the expansion will raise consumption by another 3
billion yuan (360 million U.S. dollars)," said Li Shouxin, deputy
director of the SDPC's Social Development Department.
</P>
<P>
Chinese banks are holding a record 6 trillion yuan (725 billion
U.S. dollars) in individual deposits and more people are willing
to splash out on their children's education, especially in the
higher education sector.
</P>
<P>
Hu Angang, a researcher at the Chinese Academy of Sciences,
said that, if people spend 10 percent of their savings on
education, that will release 600 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The expansion of enrollment will also spur on the construction
of educational infrastructure, Hu said.
</P>
<P>
The expansion will give more high school students access to
higher education.
</P>
<P>
Only 1.67 percent of Chinese have received higher education,
compared with 3 percent in India and Thailand and 21 percent in
Japan.
</P>
<P>
The expansion in enrollment will force universities to exploit
their potential fully, in both the teaching and logistical sectors,
so that they can accommodate more students.
</P>
<P>
Wu Qidi, president of Tongji University in Shanghai, said that
in most Chinese universities, the teacher: student ratio is about
1:8, compared with 1:14 in developed countries, so there is scope
for adjustment, the paper reports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
