<HEADLINE> Chile Says Argentina Backs It on Whether to Attend Ibero-American Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Chilean Foreign Minister Juan
Gabriel Valdes said Wednesday that Argentine President Carlos
Menem would follow Chile's suit concerning the Ibero-American
Summit, to be held in Cuba at the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
Valdes said this after returning from a visit to Argentina at
the beginning of the week, when Menem said he would do the same if
Chilean President Eduardo Frei does not attend the summit.
</P>
<P>
Frei has suspended any decision related to his participation in
the summit, because of the way Spain has interpreted a document
which limits the extra-territorial law signed at the last Ibero-
American summit in Portugal, the minister noted.
</P>
<P>
Spain, to be present at the meeting, detained Chile's lifetime
senator Augusto Pinochet last year in a London hospital and has
not initiated an extradition process.
</P>
<P>
Valdes said Chile's reluctance to attend the summit has nothing
to do with the summit itself, adding his country has been a highly
active participant in such gatherings. 
</P>
</TEXT>
