<HEADLINE> Vietnamese Leaders Affirm to Boost Vietnam-Cambodia Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Vietnamese party and state leaders
affirmed to boost Vietnam-Cambodia friendship and cooperation
during their meeting with visiting Cambodian Senate Chairman Chea
Sim in Hanoi on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
During his meeting with Chea Sim, Vietnamese President Tran Duc
Luong said that the Vietnamese people believe and resolve to
implement accords reached by the two countries, particularly those
stated in the Joint Declaration issued during the visit to
Cambodia by Vietnamese Communist Party General Secretary Le Kha
Phieu last month.
</P>
<P>
The Vietnamese president said he hoped that the two Governments
would soon sign an agreement on common border line and that
favorable conditions would be created for the Vietnamese nationals
living in Cambodia to stabilize their lives.
</P>
<P>
General Secretary of the Communist Party of Vietnam Le Kha
Phieu in his meeting with Chea Sim applauded the Cambodian
National Assembly and Senate's intention to set up a group of
Cambodia-Vietnam friendship parliamentarians.
</P>
<P>
Phieu said he hoped that the two countries' legislative bodies
would boost cooperation, contributing to the implementation of
agreements stated in the June, 1999, Vietnam-Cambodia Joint
Declaration.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese Prime Minister Phan Van Khai told the Cambodian
Senate chairman that he hoped that Vietnam and Cambodia would
strengthen their solidarity, friendship and cooperation for
development to enter together into the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
Chairman Samdech Chea Sim expressed his pleasure at the fine
steps of cooperation between the two countries in recent years.
</P>
<P>
The Cambodian leader spoke highly of the Vietnamese
Government's efforts in successfully hosting the sixth ASEAN
Summit and effectively assisting Cambodia to join the
organization.
</P>
<P>
Vietnamese Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Nguyen
Manh Cam also met in the same day with the Cambodian Senate
chairman, who began a five-day official visit to Vietnam on
Tuesday as the guest of Vietnamese National Assembly Chairman Nong
Duc Manh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
