<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Economic Zone to Take Environment into GDP Account (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, July 22 (Xinhua) -- China's largest economic zone, the
southernmost island province of Hainan, will become the country's
"ecological avant-garde" in bringing environment considerations
into accounts of local economic growth.
</P>
<P>
According to a proposal sent by Hainan to the State
Environmental Protection Administration (SEPA), an environment
index will be added to other economic figures when calculating the
province's gross domestic product (GDP) growth rate.
</P>
<P>
The proposal is under official appraisal and is expected to go
into effect.
</P>
<P>
"China is pinning high hopes on Hainan to avoid conflict
between development and the environment, something which has
become serious in many of the country's fledgling urban areas,"
said Cui Shuhong, an official with SEPA's Ecological Department.
</P>
<P>
In a detailed plan for protecting the environment of this
tropical island, the forest coverage will be extended from 50
percent or 600,000 hectares to 65 percent of the total area in 30
years, and the use of clean energy such as solar, wind, natural
gas and methane, will be greatly increased.
</P>
<P>
Officials in Hainan have created a blueprint for the rapidly
growing economic zone with agriculture, tourism, and high-tech
industries as the backbone, and in which industrial pollution is
forbidden and the quality of air, rivers, and sea water is assured.
</P>
<P>
"A sound ecological environment is the most valuable resource
for Hainan, appealing to both investors and tourists. It is
worthwhile to sustain this advantage at the expense of one to two
percentage points of GDP growth rate in the short run," said Lin
Shunkun, vice director of the environment department at the
provincial government.
</P>
<P>
He said that more than one hundred sugar and rubber mills will
be closed down in line with the environmental protection project.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Economic Zone to Take Environment into GDP Account (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Jin Jianming, a scholar with the Chinese Academy of Engineering
and one of the experts in charge of the project appraisal, called
Hainan's initiative a "creative breakthrough," changing the old
concept rooted in people's minds that ecological resources are
cheap and communal.
</P>
<P>
Jin pointed out that this obsolete idea is a driving force
behind the common mistake of accelerating economic development at
the expense of the environment.
</P>
<P>
"Most enterprises would feel reluctant to take the
environmental cost into business accounting, and would regard it
as a burden," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that Hainan's plan is an advanced method for
coordinating the development of the economy with environmental
concerns.
</P>
<P>
China has been investing heavily in environmental protection
projects, with appropriations in this area accounting for one
percent of the GDP last year, a figure first among developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
The effect of these efforts, however, has not been obvious, as
many places in China are faced with deteriorating environments,
partly attributable to the ravages of human activities, according
to the SEPA's report for 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government is expecting Hainan to set an example by
stimulating environmental protection efforts by economic means,
Jin noted.
</P>
<P>
Jilin Province in the northeast and Yunnan in the southwest
have both moved to follow suit by introducing higher
environmental protection standards, according to SEPA sources.
</P>
<P>
China has pledged to avert the further deterioration of its
environment by year 2000 and bring soil erosion and
desertification under control by 2010. This goal is readily
achievable with the installation of additional measures such as
those planned for Hainan Province.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
