<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. House Approves Funds to Boost Embassy Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives voted Wednesday to pay for strengthening security
at U.S. embassies around the world one year after the bomb attacks
on two U.S. embassies in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The bill, passed easily by a voice vote, authorized 1.4 billion
U.S. dollars to protect U.S. diplomatic missions from the threat
of international terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The bill noted that security at half the 250 U.S. facilities
abroad is considered inadequate.
</P>
<P>
"American facilities abroad are under threat as they never have
been before," said Republican lawmaker Benjamin Gilman, chairman
of the House International Relations Committee.
</P>
<P>
The legislation also addressed concern over the response of U.S.
law enforcement units to crisis abroad.
</P>
<P>
Under the bill, the Federal Bureau of Investigation is
authorized to immediately lease an aircraft for sending agents to
the site of a crisis.
</P>
<P>
At least 224 people, including 12 Americans, were killed and
thousands injured as U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania were
bombed by terrorists last August.
</P>
<P>
Several embassies have been closed for brief periods in recent
weeks because of security lapses or new threats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ngeny Steals Limelight at IAAF Golden Athletics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's Noah Ngeny continued to
challenge the middle-distance records at the Paris Golden League
athletics meeting on Wednesday, clocking the fastest 1,500 meters
this season.
</P>
<P>
Ngeny, who pushed Hicham El Guerrouj to the mile world record
in Rome two weeks ago and narrowly missed breaking Sebastian Coe's
1,000m mark at the weekend in Nice, has been the revelation this
season, having also clocked the top four 1,500m times this year.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old Ngeny powered past reigning Olympic and three-
time world champion Noureddine Morceli in the final 300 meters,
storming home in three minutes 28.84 seconds which was the seventh
fastest 1,500m ever run and a new Kenyan national record.
</P>
<P>
The meet began with seven athletes chasing a share of the 1
million U.S. dollars Golden League jackpot and finished with only
four, American sprint queen Marion Jones, Romania's Gabriela Szabo,
Denmark's Wilson Kipketer and Kenya's Bernard Barmasai still in
the hunt for a big payday.
</P>
<P>
Jones enjoyed her 18 consecutive 200m victory in a time of 21.
00, beating France's European champion Christine Arron, the 100m
European champion and record holder, to a distant fourth in 22.47.
</P>
<P>
Szabo claimed a season's best time in the 3,000m in 8:25.59
with a powerful last 100 meters, shaving almost two seconds off
the previous best time of the season.
</P>
<P>
World record holder Kipketer produced his third 800m Golden
League victory of the season in 1:44.89 after losing a shoe in the
final sprint.
</P>
<P>
Barmasai, the 3,000m steeplechase world record holder, was also
an easy winner, clocking a comfortable 8:05.71, almost two seconds
clear of Morocco's Ali Ezzine.
</P>
<P>
Double Olympic champion Svetlana Masterkova of Russia finished
a distant fourth in the 800m with a time of 1:59.25 to stop her
chance of athletics' biggest payday.
</P>
<P>
Jamaica's James Beckford brought American Erik Walder's Golden
League dreams to an end with a victory in the long jump of 8.42m
while Walder flew 7.78m.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
