<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Officials Close Pantani Test Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Italian sports officials decided on
Wednesday to stop their inquiries into a blood test failure by
national cycling hero Marco Pantani.
</P>
<P>
The anti-doping department of the national Olympic committee (
CONI), which in Italy doubles as the sports ministry, ordered its
inquisition after Pantani was kicked off the Tour of Italy last
month.
</P>
<P>
Pantani had been leading the race but was banned from starting
the penultimate stage at Madonna di Campiglio on June 5 after a
test showed his red corpuscles count to be 52 percent, above the
safety limit of 50.
</P>
<P>
A high count suggests the use of Erythropoietin (EPO), which
boosts the number of red blood cells which carry oxygen around the
body, and markedly improves endurance. However, failing a test
does not prove EPO use.
</P>
<P>
After weeks of investigations, the CONI officials decided no
further inquiry of the athlete which meant the case is now closed.
</P>
<P>
Pantania plans to return in time for the world championship in
Italy in October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
