<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Reiterates One-China Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
reiterated the one-China policy on Wednesday as Lee Teng-hui's
redefinition of the cross-strait relationship was refuted on both
sides of the straits.
</P>
<P>
"Our policy is clear. We favor the one-China policy. We favor
the cross-strait dialogues," Clinton told a White House press
conference.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan's Lee Teng-hui claimed on July 9 that the cross-straits
relationship should be "state-to-state" or at least "special state-
to-state."
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government believes that Lee's flagrant
redefinition of the cross-straits relationship exposed his
political malice and intention to undermine the Chinese
territorial integrity and sovereignty and his attempt to separate
Taiwan from China.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said the one-China policy is not a "puzzling fiction."
And although Taiwan and the Chinese mainland are not unified today,
the Chinese take a long view, he added.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese tend to take a long view of these things and have
made clear a sensitivity to the different system that exists on
Taiwan and a willingness to find ways to accommodate it, as they
did in working with Hong Kong, and perhaps even going beyond that,
" Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"So I think the important thing is ...they need to take the
time necessary to work this out between themselves in a peaceful
way," he said.
</P>
<P>
Explaining the reason on the delay of a Pentagon mission to
Taiwan, Clinton said, "I didn't think this was the best time to do
something which might excite either one side or the other."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0303 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Reports 2 Billion U.S. Dollar Surplus for June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- The Brazilian government
registered a primary surplus of some 2.04 billion U.S. dollars in
June, the Finance Ministry said in a report released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
With the positive results recorded in June, the government has
accumulated a primary surplus of 7.22 billion dollars in the first
half of the year, compared with only 1.70 billion dollars in the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
The favorable balance in June was a result of a surplus of 2.24
billion dollars in the National Treasury and deficits of 184.3
million dollars and 11.2 million dollars in the Social Provision
and the Central Bank respectively.
</P>
<P>
The surplus accounted for 2.6 percent of the country's gross
domestic product (GDP), compared with 0.4 percent in the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
Also in the report, the Finance Ministry said Brazil's total
debt amounted to 102 billion dollars in June, with more than one
third being internal debt.
</P>
<P>
The figure represents 19.3 percent of the GDP, up 3.3
percentage points from that of the same month in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
