<HEADLINE> Cuba Celebrates Hemingway Centenary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, July 21 (Xinhua) -- Cultural circles in Cuba launched a
variety of activities on Wednesday to celebrate the 100th birthday
of late U.S. writer Ernest Hemingway.
</P>
<P>
Lectures, conferences and book presentations are among the
events dedicated to the life and work of Hemingway, who lived in
Cuba for 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Hemingway, winner of the Nobel Prize for Literature in 1954,
was born on July 21, 1899, in Oak Park, Illinois, and died on July
2, 1961, in Ketchum, Idaho.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. writer was at the forefront of cultural circles in
Cuba, because some of his novels were inspired by his life
experiences on the island.
</P>
<P>
Hemingway is described by book critics as an author whose
novels have a strong sense of realism in a concise and direct
style.
</P>
<P>
Among his works are "The Old Man and the Sea" (1952), "For Whom
the Bells Toll" (1940), "To Have and Have Not" (1937), and "
Islands in the Gulf", a posthumous edition published in 1970.
</P>
<P>
According to critics, Hemingway is the second most popular
English-writing author to have his books translated into other
languages, after British authoress Agatha Christie.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. author went to Cuba at the age of 28, in April of the
year 1928. For nine years, he lived in the Hotel "Ambos Mundos" in
Havana, in room 511. The hotel was later converted into a museum.
</P>
<P>
The author, known in Cuba as "Papa," later moved to live in San
Francisco de Paula, on the outskirts of Havana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
