<HEADLINE> Highlights of Beijing-Based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
People's Daily
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing said yesterday that China
has to step up the pursuit of an active fiscal policy in the
second half of the year.
</P>
<P>
In a written speech read to a national conference on China's
finance work, Li said that China has decided to take a series of
major measures to step up the active fiscal policy in the second
half of the year, all of which are designed to promote consumption,
investment and exports, accelerate economic restructuring, and
maintain a rapid, healthy and sustainable growth of the national
economy
</P>
<P>
-- The Association for Relations Across the Taiwan Straits (
ARATS) Wednesday condemned Lee Teng-hui's separatist remarks and
urged some leaders of its Taiwan counterpart, the Straits
Exchanges Foundation (SEF), to stop attempts to split the
motherland and return to the "one China" principle.
</P>
<P>
Council members of ARATS convened a meeting in Beijing
yesterday and stressed that the "one China" principle is the
foundation for the mutual development of cross-Straits relations
and the peaceful reunification of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
 Xinhua Daily Telegraph
</P>
<P>
-- President Jiang Zemin has signed an order for implementation
of the "Regulations Governing Nonmilitary Cadres Serving in the
People's Liberation Army".
</P>
<P>
The 9-chapter regulations stipulate explicitly the function,
management, training and fixed time of service for nonmilitary
cadres serving in the PLA, as well as policies for selecting
cadres, uniforms, and ranking.
</P>
<P>
-- The separatist forces and the handful of "independence for
Taiwan" activists on China's island province of Taiwan are doomed
to be pilloried by history, along with Lee Teng-hui, says a Xinhua
commentary entitled "Separatism Is A Dead End" yesterday.
</P>
<P>
As is well known, Lee is to blame for the trumpeting of "
independence for Taiwan" because he has gone all out to discourage
and suppress those on the island who advocate the reunification of
the motherland and oppose separatism, the article says, referring
to a saying widespread there that it is Lee Teng-hui who has
breast fed the "independence for Taiwan" forces.
</P>
<P>
China Daily
</P>
<P>
-- The long-brewing telecom service reorganization, which
targets ending the monopoly of China Telecom and introduces
competition will be completed in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
Symbolic of the change was the country's mobile phone code
growing to 11 digits at midnight last night.
</P>
<P>
-- China yesterday welcomed what it called the "wise decision"
by Papua New Guinea's new government to cancel its communique on "
diplomatic ties" with Taiwan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
