<HEADLINE> U.S. Congress Urged to Treat Cigars Like Cigarettes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 21 (Xinhua) -- U.S. federal regulators on
Wednesday urged the Congress to mandate tough new health warnings
on cigar labels and place them on the same regulatory footing as
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Trade Commission (FTC), the government's chief
consumer protection agency, required a ban on television and radio
cigar advertising to dispel the notion that cigars are a safe
alternative to cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
Total advertising and promotional expenditures for cigars
increased 32 percent to reach 41 million dollars in 1997 from 30.9
million dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
After a 20-year decline, cigar consumption in the United States
increased to 5.4 billion in 1998 from 3.4 billion in 1993,
government figures show.
</P>
<P>
"Regular cigar smokers are at risk of mouth and throat cancer
similar to that of cigarette smokers," said FTC Chairman Robert
Pitofsky.
</P>
<P>
There may be people under the misimpression that if they switch
to cigars they are in safe harbors, he added.
</P>
<P>
The commission reported a 15 percent increase in cigar unit
sales and a 43 percent increase in dollar sales from 1996 to 1997,
based on information from the five leading domestic cigar
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
Cigar makers said sales, based on wholesale price, rose from
613 million dollars to 876 million dollars from 1996 to 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0314 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Economic Recovery Far From Assured: WB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 22 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank warned Indonesia
that its economic recovery was far from assured, despite
heartening progress in economic stabilization efforts, The Jakarta
Post reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The bank cited the huge unresolved debts of the private sector,
widespread corporate distress, continuing difficulties in the
banking sector, an unacceptably low level of output, and
increasing poverty as the most pressing problems facing the
country.
</P>
<P>
"This is no time for complacency," said World Bank country
director for Indonesia Mark Baird when releasing the bank's annual
country report on Indonesia here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report recommended three policy priorities to consolidate
stabilization gains in the short term, including pressing ahead
with bank and corporate restructuring, protecting the poor, and
careful management of fiscal balances.
</P>
<P>
The report, titled "Indonesia From Crisis to Opportunity", will
serve as a briefing report for the upcoming July 27-28
Consultative Group on Indonesia (CGI) donors meeting in Paris.
</P>
<P>
The report said the proximate cause of the country's economic
crisis, the large amount of short-term private sector unhedged
external debt, remained unresolved.
</P>
<P>
"Most of these debts are owed by distressed corporates, many of
which are insolvent or have ceased operations," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia's private sector has some 72 billion U.S. dollars in
overseas debts.
</P>
<P>
The bank said public (government) debt had jumped from 24
percent of gross domestic product (GDP) at the end of June, 1997,
to 60 percent at the end of June, 1998, and was expected to reach
102 percent by end-1999, or a fourfold increase from the
pre-crisis period. Official foreign debts alone are now estimated
at almost 70 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The bank said the economy was still operating at 15 to 20
percent below capacity.
</P>
<P>
"Resolving these challenges will require steady and determined
economic reforms, placing a premium on policy continuity as the
country goes through political transition," the bank said.
</P>
<P>
The bank stressed that in the banking sector the main focus
should be on restructuring state banks, strengthening bank
supervision, and accelerating the recovery of various assets under
the Indonesian Bank Restructuring Agency.
</P>
<P>
The bank also stressed the need for Indonesia to manage fiscal
balances carefully by placing greater emphasis on domestic
resource mobilization and reduced borrowing, especially from
abroad.
</P>
<P>
The report identifies three medium-term policy priorities:
develop and deepen institutions, especially the legal and judicial
system and the civil service; strengthen markets and market
institutions; and ensure growth is environmentally sustainable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990722.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Help Court to Deal With New Type of Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 22 (Xinhua) -- A court in the Chinese capital is
seeking more expert assistance to deal with cases in new areas
such as intellectual property and computer technology, according
to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Municipal Higher People's Court (BMHPC) formed an
expert consultation commission Wednesday that includes 48 legal
experts joined by others with special expertise in areas such as
intellectual property and computer technology.
</P>
<P>
The report said that a quickly developing knowledge-based
economy is forcing the court to seek more expert assistance.
</P>
<P>
An intellectual property court under the BMHPC invited experts
to help them with some complicated technical problems encountered
during trials in 1996. But this time, the system will be made
permanent.
</P>
<P>
"Although our judges are experienced and well trained, you can
not expect them to be experts in every high-tech field," said the
court president Zhang Lumin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
